<HEADLINE> Nepali Cabinet Expanded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government today
expanded its present eight-member cabinet to a 34-member one after
it took power nearly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the Royal Palace this
evening, King Birendra expanded the cabinet, or council of
ministers, on the recommendation of Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand, who assumed office on March 12 along with the
compact cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Chand, a senior leader of the National Democratic Party (RPP),
earlier formed his three-party government with the participation
of the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPM-UML)
and the Nepal Goodwill Party (NSP) to replace the former
government under Sher Bahadur Deuba of the Nepali Congress (NC)
party.
</P>
<P>
The new government won a vote of confidence last week in the
lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Among the members of the newly expanded cabinet including 25
ministers and 9 state ministers, 22 are from the CPN-UML, 10 from
the RPP and 2 from the NSP.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chand will also look after the Ministries of
Royal Palace Affairs, Defense, Water Resources, Land Reforms and
Management, and Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
While Deputy Prime Minister Bamdev Gautum, a CPN-UML leader,
will also hold the portfolio of home minister, according to the
press release.
</P>
<P>
The following are other major ministers and their portfolios:
</P>
<P>
Finance Rabindra Nath Sharma (RPP)
</P>
<P>
Women and Social Welfare  Sahana Pradhan (CPN-UML)
</P>
<P>
Local Development Amrit Kumar Bohara (CPN-UML)
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Prakash Chandra Lohani (RPP)
</P>
<P>
Information and Communications  Jhalanath Khanal (CPN-UML)
</P>
<P>
Housing and Planning  Kamal Thapa (RPP)
</P>
<P>
Supplies  Gajendra Narayan Singh (NSP)
</P>
<P>
Tourism and Civil Aviation  Salim Mian Ansari (CPN-UML)
</P>
<P>
Education Devi Prasad Ojha (CPN-UML)
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Ram Krishna Acharya (RPP)
</P>
</TEXT>
