<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Officials Required to Report Personal Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The General Office of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and the State
Council have issued regulations on the process to be followed by
leading officials when reporting important personal matters to
concerned departments.
</P>
<P>
The regulations are intended to strengthen the management and
supervision over the leading officials and advance the build-up of
a cleaner government, according to a circular issued by the
General Office.
</P>
<P>
Under the regulations, leading officials must report to
concerned departments:
</P>
<P>
-- on the building, trading or leasing of any house by
themselves, their spouse or children living with them;
</P>
<P>
-- on the weddings of themselves or funerals of their close
relatives administered by the officials;
</P>
<P>
-- on the marriage with foreigners by themselves or their
children, and their spouse or children's traveling and residing
overseas;
</P>
<P>
-- on their traveling overseas for private reasons and their
activities during the overseas stay.
</P>
<P>
The officials are also asked to report when their spouse or
children are dealt with by law enforcement agencies or are
involved in crime, and when their spouse or children open their
own business or contract the operation of state or
collectively-run enterprises, or are employed as administrative
personnel of foreign-funded enterprises or representative offices
of overseas enterprises in China.
</P>
<P>
Those who fail to report or make false reports will be
reprimanded and ordered to correct their errors within a limited
period of time, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials mentioned in the regulations are defined as
those serving in leading positions in party organizations,
people's congresses, administrative bodies, people's political
consultative conferences, courts and procuratorial bodies, those
who are on par with the rank of deputy county magistrate in social
bodies or institutions, officials above the middle level in large
state-run enterprises, and leading officials representing the
state-run investors in large or medium-sized enterprises that
practice the corporate system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
