<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Disease Presents New Challenge to Human Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 24 (Xinhua) -- An infectious disease that has
plagued mankind for several millenia is likely to launch a new
global offensive against the human race.
</P>
<P>
An official with the World Health Organization announced here
today that the disease, tuberculosis (TB), which became curable
since effective drugs were developed in the 1940s, again became
the top killer among infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
"Closely linked with the emergence of multi-drug resistant
strains of TB and the HIV/AIDS epidemic, TB has re-emerged as a
major public health problem in both developed and developing
countries," A.H. Schnur, acting representative of WHO's Beijing
Office, said at a seminar marking the 115th anniversary of Dr
Robert Koch's discovery of the bacillus which causes TB.
</P>
<P>
Among 1.7 billion people who have been infected by TB, 20
million have developed into TB patients, and about 3.5 million of
them die every year, according to WHO's statistics.
</P>
<P>
The organization also predicted that in the coming decade
another 90 million people will become TB patients and more than 30
million will die.
</P>
<P>
Dr Koch's discovery may have marked a vital success in humans'
perpetual battle against TB. But now they are being challenged by
a new question -- Will people win another round in this battle?
</P>
<P>
"His (Koch's) discovery opened the way to diagnosing, curing
and possibly even eliminating TB. But progress since 1882 has been
painfully slow," A.H.Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
"While drugs are now available to cure TB, they are not
affordable or not accessible to those most in need," he
explained. "Even when treatment is available, patients often start
treatment and stop ... before the disease is fully cured."
</P>
<P>
Incorrect TB treatment would develop multidrug-resistant TB,
which means even more expensive and difficult treatment, and will
accelerate the speed at which TB infection spreads, said Prof. Tu
Dehua, director of the Beijing Institute for Tuberculosis Control.
</P>
<P>
Many other factors are also causing the global epidemic of TB,
such as dual TB/HIV epidemics, more chances of infection produced
by frequent transnational travelling, and people's ignorance, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Facing the new challenge, the last and the best chance for the
people may be DOTS, or directly observed treatment, short course,
which was introduced by WHO as the only way to reduce the
transmission of TB and lower the number of deaths due to the
disease.
</P>
<P>
"Under the strategy, patients receive their drug dosage daily
under the supervision of health staff to ensure that they take the
medicine for the full six month period usually required to cure
TB," A.H.Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
Cure rates in programs using DOTS have been shown to be much
higher than for programs not using DOTS, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has kicked off the world's biggest DOTS-using TB control
project since 1992, covering a population of 560 million in 12
provinces and autonomous regions, according to China's Ministry of
Health.
</P>
<P>
The project has helped cure 92 percent of pulmonary TB
patients, seven percentage points higher than the year 2000 goal
set by WHO.
</P>
<P>
"China's high cure rates and successful use of the DOTS
strategy has been an example for the rest of the world,"
A.H.Schnur said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
