<HEADLINE> New Education Curriculum Unveiled in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A new curriculum aimed at
breaking with the past and meeting the challenges of the 21st
century in South Africa was launched by Education Minister
Sibusiso Bengu in Cape Town today.
</P>
<P>
At a launching ceremony in Parliament, Bengu said Curriculum
2005, which has taken two years to develop, would introduce a
life-long people-centered education system for all throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of this new curriculum will play a major
role in helping to transform our country into one in which we all
want to live by producing thinking, caring learners," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Bengu said he was confident that the new curriculum would be a
giant step forward in ensuring quality education for all the
people in South Africa, and it would also be embraced by all
those who have a part in the learning process.
</P>
<P>
However, the new curriculum was immediately criticized by the
opposition National Party (NP) who claimed the initiative lacked
transparency and inclusivity.
</P>
<P>
NP education spokesman Renier Schoeman said "It is highly
regrettable that the Department of Education has chosen to deal
with this major step in what appears to be a non-transparent,
non-inclusive way." 
</P>
</TEXT>
