<HEADLINE> Polish President on Russian-U.S. Helsiki Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski has said Russia and the United States had narrowed
their differences over the planned expansion of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) at the Helsinki summit, the local press
reported.
</P>
<P>
"Poland does not oppose that the United States and other NATO
members sign special treaties with Russia," Kwasniewski was quoted
as telling a Finnish television last Friday by the Polish
newspaper Rzeczpospolita Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The signing of special agreements between an enlarged NATO and
Russia and Ukraine would be conducive to the European security
system, Kwasniewski said.
</P>
<P>
Bronislaw Geremek, chairman of the Commission of the Foreign
Affairs in Poland's parliament, said on the same day that nothing
bad had happened in Helsinki for the time being.
</P>
<P>
"No decision made there (in Helsinki) goes against the
interests of the Polish nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Janusz Onyszkiewicz, Poland's former defense minister,
said that there still existed questions after the summit, which
caused concerns and needed to be clarified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
