<HEADLINE> Zaire Crisis Not So Serious as Media Put It: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Minister of Foreign Affairs
Rebecca Kataga has said here that "the crisis in Zaire is no
longer as serious as international press would like to make it",
a local radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks last night on her arrival at Lome, the
capital of Togo, to attend a ministerial meeting on the Zairean
crisis before the Wednesday summit of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
"We need negotiations as soon as possible involving all
factions in Zaire", she said, adding that "it is the time for
them to sit down to work their solutions all together".
</P>
<P>
The Zairean government has accused Uganda and Rwanda of
sending their army to fight with the rebels led by Lauren Kabila
in eastern Zaire. Both Uganda and Rwanda have rejected the
charge.
</P>
<P>
Michel Dupuis, the adviser for African affairs of French
President Jacques Chirac, is in Lome for the OAU summit
representing Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The presence of France at the summit shows its great interest
in this matter, Dupuis said. He said that he wishes the summit a
success.
</P>
<P>
France has been calling for foreign intervention in Zaire
since the conflict started last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
