<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Continued in West Bank, Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers opened fire
and wounded a Palestinian today as violent confrontations
continued in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip between Israeli
soldiers and Palestinians protesters.
</P>
<P>
In Gaza Strip today, Israeli soldiers seriously wounded a
Palestinian riding on a donkey in Tel Sultan this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted security sources as saying that the man
did not have any identity papers with him when asked to
present them, and he then ignored orders to stop and kept
riding off when the Israeli soldiers opened fire on him.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon, a large number of Palestinian youths begun
to throw stones at Israeli troops stationed at Rachel's Tomb,
in Palestinian controlled Bethlehem in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The violent confrontations began during the early afternoon
hours, and as the number of Palestinian participants increased,
Israeli army evacuated the Jewish worshipers from Rachel's Tomb.
</P>
<P>
Later, the Israeli army declared the area a closed military
zone, barring Israelis and tourists from entering Bethlehem from
the southern Jerusalem neighborhood of Gilo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two firebombs and stones were thrown at an
Israeli army patrol in Rafiah in the Gaza Strip early this
afternoon, but no one was injured.
</P>
<P>
Following a weekend of violence, once again a large number
of Palestinian demonstrators confronted with Israeli soldiers in
front of the Bet Hadassah building in the Jewish area of
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
On various occasions, Palestinian police tried to help calm
the angry Palestinian protesters, who have been demonstrating in
the past four days, during which more than 100 people were
injured.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been increasing between Israel and the
Palestinians, following Friday's suicide bombing attack in Tel
Aviv, and continuous confrontations between Israeli soldiers and
Palestinians protesters.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Moussa Ranimat, 28, of Kafr Tsurif near Hebron,
detonated a three-kilogram TNT bomb packed with nails and
pieces of metal in a coffee shop in the center of Tel
Aviv, killing three women and wounding 48 others.
</P>
<P>
A closure was imposed on the West Bank and Gaza Strip
by the Israeli army immediately following the attack, barring
Palestinians from entering Israel.
</P>
<P>
The latest unrest came after Israeli government decided to
go ahead with the construction of a new Jewish neighborhood
in Jerusalem, despite strong condemnation warnings from the
Palestine National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Palestinians term the construction, which started Tuesday
afternoon, as another Israeli attempt to Judaize Jerusalem, a city
which the Palestinians see as the capital for their future
independent state.
</P>
<P>
PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat said that Israel's insistence to
build on Jabal Abu Ghneim (Har Homa) "violates the signed
accords, and contradicts the Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu rejected
allegations that his government's decision to build Har Homa
created the conditions for the Friday suicide bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu fingered the PNA as being responsible for
the attack, and demanded the PNA to rearrest 150 leaders of
Hamas and Islamic Jihad who have recently been released.
</P>
<P>
PNA officials condemned the suicide bombing attack, but
rejected charges that Arafat had given Hamas a "green light,"
by releasing some of the organization's activists. the PNA today
also rejected an Israeli demand to crack down Islamic militants in
the PNA controlled areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
