<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Gulf War Reparations Already in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said today the first portion
of 1991 Gulf War reparations, amounting to 58.3 million
U.S. dollars, has already reached the Central Bank of Egypt from
the United Nations Reparations Fund.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Labor and Immigration Ahmed el-Amawi said the
ministry is currently working to write out 23,000 checks for
those who are to take advantage of this first tranche.
</P>
<P>
The total of the reparations which are overdue for Egyptians
is up to 823 million dollars, Amawi said, noting that the
remaining amount is to be transferred later with the continuous
selling of the Iraqi oil.
</P>
<P>
This move came within the context of the oil-for-food deal
concluded by the U.N. and Iraq in December to allow the latter
to sell 2 billion dollars of oil in six months to ease the impact
of trade sanctions imposed on Iraq for its August 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In line with the deal, 30 percent of the Iraqi oil sales are
to be paid to people who lost their life savings or jobs due to
the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage, 32 billion dollars will be paid to those
who were forced to leave Iraq and Kuwait during the war.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 23,300 Egyptians will get 58.3 million dollars
from the delivery.
</P>
<P>
The total of the reparations, estimated at 200 billion
dollars, will be paid out of the returns of Iraq's oil sales over
20 years.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will have access to about 1.3 billion dollars over six
months after funneling 30 percent to the fund for Gulf War
reparations and meeting other U.N. costs.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. fund is expected to take several years in examining
the papers of those who have demanded to be compensated for their
losses in the war.
</P>
<P>
In the 90 days till March 10, Iraq exported 52.3 million
barrels of oil worth an estimated 1.07 billion dollars, including
pipeline fees to Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
