<HEADLINE> S. Africa Supports OAU's Change of Objective: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, March 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa fully
supported the Organization of African Unity (OAU) transforming
its objective from the liberation of the African continent to its
development, a top official said today.
</P>
<P>
This new spirit entered the OAU after South Africa joined the
organiztion, South African Press Association quoted Foreign
Affairs Deputy Director-General for Africa Anthony Mongale as
saying.
</P>
<P>
When the OAU was founded in 1963, its objective had been the
total liberation of the African continent. This had now been
achieved, Mongale said in Cape Town, the legislative capital of
South Afria.
</P>
<P>
Referring to diplomatic relations, Mongale said South Africa
now had 22 foreign missions in Africa, including all Southern
African Development Community states, while it hosted 33 African
missions.
</P>
<P>
This was a "great achievement in such a short time of our
democracy", Mongale said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Deputy Director-General for Europe and America
Tebogo Mafole also announced today that Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki would sign an agreement with the French government in June
to establish a binational commission between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee, Mafole said
that a document on bilateral Economic Commissions were being
signed in France, through which cooperation between South Africa
and France would be further promoted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
