<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commission President Says EMU Will Start on Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) executive
Commission President Jacques Santer today voiced his conviction
that the European Monetary Union (EMU) would be launched as
planned on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC radio interview today, Santer dismissed
suggestions that even Germany, the powerhouse of European
integration, might not be ready in time and the Maastricht
Treaty's criteria for EMU entry would be fudged.
</P>
<P>
"I am quite confident that it will start on time on the basis
of the criteria of Maastricht and with a significant number of
(EU) member states," he said.
</P>
<P>
Santer made it clear that Germany and France would start in the
first wave to join the EMU, but he added there was hard work to be
done in achieving the target.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether there would have to be fudging if some EU
countries such as Spain and Italy were to make it in time, he
said, "No, we are not fudging the criteria. Not at all." 
</P>
</TEXT>
