<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Scores Success in Family Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has scored a major
achievement in its family planning programs within 10 years,
Health and Child Welfare Minister Timothy Stamps said here today.
</P>
<P>
Stamps, who was a guest speaker at the Zimbabwe Staff College
in Harare, told soldiers attending a joint command and staff
course that the family planning had become an important health
care component of his ministry.
</P>
<P>
On the average, a Zimbabwean family now has 5.4 children, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The southern African country has also scored major successes
in eliminating malnutrition among children, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Good strides had been made in direct prevention of the six
child killer diseases of polio, diphtheria, whooping cough,
tetanus, tuberculosis and measles," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
