<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's National Blood Stocks Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's national blood stocks
have improved significantly this year with the National Blood
Transfusion Service (NBTS) meeting at least 80 percent of the
national needs as hiv sero-prevalence among regular donors
declines.
</P>
<P>
NBTS medical director Macleod Chitiyo said today the high
prevalence of hiv infection in the community had no impact on
blood donations.
</P>
<P>
"The hiv sero-prevalence in blood donors is actually going
down. The increasing cases of hiv have had no impact on blood
donations as evidenced by the number of blood collections which
have risen from 74,000 in 1994/95 to 77,000 in 1995/96," Chitiyo
said.
</P>
<P>
Chitiyo said hiv sero-positivity among donors had dropped from
2.24 percent in 1995 to 1.54 percent last year while the rate
among regular donors was even lower at about 0.52 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hiv prevalence levels among the 16 to 19 years age group
donors, mostly school children, had also dropped from 0.81
percent in 1995 to 0.68 percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of TB Cases in Zambia on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of new cases of
tuberculosis (tb) in Zambia rose from 16,863 in the year 1990 to
33,553 in the year 1995, central province acting permanent
secretary G. Akafekwa revealed today.
</P>
<P>
While addressing a function to mark the work tb day in his
province's capital Kabwe, Akafekwa observed that tb has become
one of the leading causes of mortality as it accounts for 10 to
13 percent of adult deaths in Zambia and the spread of the
disease has been on the increase in the country.
</P>
<P>
He called for a dual strategy of tb control and hiv/Aids
prevention since the Aids pandemic and the tb epidemic are locked
in a vicious circle of mutual reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
He challenged the mass media to sensitise the public on the
need to eradicate tb while publicizing the hiv/Aids pandemic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
