<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council of Europe to Protect Aid to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Europe today
welcomed the ongoing efforts of certain European Union member
states to assemble a multinational protection force for Albania to
help create a secure environment for the safe provision of
international assistance.
</P>
<P>
In a series of draft conclusions adopted here today, the
council also considered it important to assist Albania in the
re-establishment of a viable police force and decided that the EU
would support this process through certain appropriate measures
such as training.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of the report of the EU mission that visited
Albania from March 17 to 19, the council agreed that the EU had a
"very substantial" role to play in helping the country to return
to political stability and internal security.
</P>
<P>
The council decided to take the initiative to set up an
advisory mission to Albania to advise on humanitarian, economic,
political and security-related developments.
</P>
<P>
In order to prepare the ground for the advisory mission, the
council said that it would dispatch an advance team without delay.
The advance team, to which representatives of other international
organizations will be invited, would make recommendations on the
composition of the advisory mission and facilitate the arrival of
humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
The council stressed that economic and financial support would
also be subject to the re-establishment of the necessary secure
environment in Albania, an Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) member country.
</P>
<P>
The council also stressed the importance of assisting this
process through appropriate monitoring and considered that the
European Community Monitoring Mission could make a contribution to
this effort.
</P>
<P>
However, up to now, both the scale and the nature of the
multinational force remain to be decided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
