<HEADLINE> TB Cases on Increase in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 24 (Xinhua) -- There has been a drastic
increase of Tuberculosis cases from 15,000 to 44,000 victimes for
the past 10 years in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Minister for Health, A. Chiduo said this at Temeke
Hospital in the city today on an event marking world TB day with
this year's theme "Directly Observed Treatment, Short course"
(DOTS) insisting close supervision on a victim.
</P>
<P>
The minister said TB had reached an alarming rate in the
country because of AIDS which started being widely spread in
1984, thus deteriolating people's immunity "defence" against the
infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania was among the first countries in Africa which
launched a special program to curb TB and leprosy in 1977. He
said the program was a great success with tremendous decrease in
TB cases from 1981 to 1983 but the achievement was interrupted by
AIDS in 1984.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, despite the increased costs in TB
treatment, the government will coninue offering the treatment
services free of charge because of the sensitivity of the disease
to the country and the world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged local and international donors to assist
the government with funds for fighting against the disease.
</P>
<P>
The minister paid tribute to world health organisation (WHO),
other donor countries and international donor agencies for their
supports.
</P>
<P>
The WHO representative to Tanzania, Dirk Warning said the WHO
was concerned about the alarming rate of TB victims in Tanzania
and would do its best by ensuring that TB facilities and
essential drugs were available, reaching the target group in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
He commended Tanzania for its speical programs against TB and
for putting into profitable use of aid from donors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
