<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Final Push on Deregulation in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union is calling on
Japan to further open its market as the Japanese government
prepares a final round of deregulation measures in one week's
time.
</P>
<P>
Horse-racing, car parts, transport services,
telecommunications, fresh fruit and starch are among the issues
where the EU is urging Japan to open its market, said a press
release issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, has engaged
in intensive discussions with Japan in order to encourage Tokyo to
take comprehensive deregulation measures in areas of interest to
European business.
</P>
<P>
"The European Commission attaches particular importance to
efforts by Japan to deregulate its economy and improve the
business environment for all companies," Sir Leon Brittan, EU
commissioner for relations with Japan, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Japanese government to make determined efforts so
that "real and tangible" results will emerge in line with Japan's
own ambitions to create a more open economy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that progress had been made on insurance, electrical
equipment, cosmetics and other areas, but the commission is
calling for one final push to deregulate other markets where
European exports to Japan are hindered.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government is due to publish the final revision of
its current three-year deregulation program at the end of March.
The EU is making a final push in the run-up in order to make the
best of it for its economic interests.
</P>
<P>
One type of market access restriction in Japan that is of
particular concern to the EU is the regulatory system which
governs business. The Japanese economy is characterized by a
complex web of regulations that restrict business opportunities.
</P>
</TEXT>
