<HEADLINE> Belgium Starts to Evacuate Its Citizens in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Belgium today began to evacuate
its citizens from Zaire, its war-torn former colony, by airlifting
paratroopers to the African country.
</P>
<P>
A total of 550 Belgian soldiers will be flown to Brazzaville,
capital of the Congo, which lies just across the Zaire river from
the Zairean capital Kinshasa, in this so-called "Green Stream"
operation.
</P>
<P>
An army spokesman was quoted as saying that the soldiers would
not move into the Zairean capital unless there was a need to do
so. In Brazzaville, the Belgian soldiers will join 650 U.S. and 40
French soldiers who are ready to evacuate their nationals.
</P>
<P>
As rebels led by Laurent Kabila have captured one fifth of the
country, Zaire's 66-year-old president Mobutu Sese Seko, who is
gravely ill with cancer, is standing another fatal risk of being
overthrown.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 7,000 Westerners are waiting to be evacuated in
Zaire, where tension is running high. There are 3,000 Belgians in
the country, including 1,150 in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian news agency Belga quoted Jean-Pol Poncelet, the
Belgian defense minister, as saying that the mission could last
more than a month. But another army official said no deadline had
actually been set. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
