<HEADLINE> Turkish National Charged with Bomb Attack and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish national was charged
here today with espionage and a bomb attack against the premises of
a Kurdish cultural center.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus news agency today, the Limassol District
Court ordered Nedjip Srichichekli, 45, arrested two weeks ago,
to remain in police custody until March 31, when he will
appear before the Court for a preliminary hearing.
</P>
<P>
The defendant was refused bail by the Court for fear that
he might escape to the northern Turkish occupied part of the
island.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the Court said Srichichekli was
charged with placing explosives in the Kurdish Association's
premises, in the southern town of Limassol, and with possession
of explosives, a time bomb, plastic explosives and a detonator
on February 10, 1996.
</P>
<P>
He is also facing charges of passing on information
concerning National Guard camps, two ports and the airport in
the western coastal town of Paphos, to two Turkish Cypriots
and a Turk, between August 1994 and February 1997.
</P>
<P>
Srichichekli is accused of gathering and handing over
information on National Guard arms acquisition program and the
Republic's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The Court also charged him with photographing restricted
areas and National Guard camps, without permission, between
February 15, 1995 and February 15, 1997 and between February
15 and March 8, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot lawyer, Sefika Durduran, was present at the
Court proceedings on behalf of Srichichekli's lawyer, Ali Dana,
but she could not speak before the Court as she is not
registered with the Cyprus Bar.
</P>
<P>
Srichichekli, along with another Turkish national Mustafa Omer
Konor and Dijan Nejip, a Turkish Cypriot, were arrested and
remanded in custody on March 8, on suspicion of spying on
Cyprus' security and military positions, but Konor and Nejip
were released Sunday for lack of evidence in espionage.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and seized northern third of the island in the wake
of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
