<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges Expatriate Businessmen to Help Homeland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Egypt kicked off the 5th Conference
for Egyptian Businessmen Abroad here today, calling on the corps
of expatriate investors to make greater contributions to the
country's development.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 Egyptian businessmen based either in Egypt or
abroad, together with seven cabinet ministers and 10 governors,
took part in the two-day annual conference that aims at
encouraging Egyptian businessmen abroad to join the all-embracing
development process in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural speech, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Agriculture Yousef Wali shed light on the new investment incentive
packages the government plans to offer to investors.
</P>
<P>
The draft law, to be examined by the People's Assembly in the
ensuing two days, includes an array of incentives, guarantees and
exemptions for investors. Privileges particularly designed for
Egyptian investors abroad will be highlighted.
</P>
<P>
The proposed legislation, according to Wali, guarantees that no
confiscation, sequestration or nationalization of investment
projects or capital will be made to protect the interests of
investors.
</P>
<P>
Wali said a 20-year tax break is offered to investors who set
up projects in the southern Nile Valley or move their existing
ventures to the new communities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Egypt gives investors full freedom to set up
projects without prior approvals by the General Investment
Authority. Reductions in customs duties will be also offered to
investors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egypt also made an attempt to clear its image
tarnished by terrorist attacks in the country, including a shooting
incident at the Europa Hotel in Cairo that killed 18 Greek
tourists last April and an attack in Qena province, which 14 lives
last week.
</P>
<P>
At the opening, Minister of Interior Hassan al-Alfy assured the
investors that terrorism leaderships have "finally" been uprooted
and stability prevails in the country.
</P>
<P>
Egypt wants the businessmen to take part in the giant
investment ventures launched by the government, such as the New
Valley Project and the Upper Egypt Development Project.
</P>
<P>
It also expect them to introduce new ideas to the country's
economic reform program and give a hand in increasing production,
augmenting exports and creating new jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
