<HEADLINE> Lebanon Calls for US Just Role in Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon called today for a "just
and pushing" role of the United States in the Middle East peace
process, and warned of a "collapse" of the process and
Washington's credibility.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz stressed here this
afternoon that what has been achieved in the peace process
generally and in the Palestinian-Israeli track particularly is
"threatened."
</P>
<P>
"We have reached a stage where even what has been
achieved on the level of the Oslo Accord, and that of the
Hebron Agreement, has become threatened," the Lebanese foreign
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz left here this afternoon for Morocco's capital of
Rabat to attend a conference of the Jerusalem Committee, and
then, on Saturday, for Cairo to participate in the conference
of Arab foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
At the Beirut International Airport, the foreign minister
reiterated a fear over a "collapse of the peace process and the
credibility of the U.S. role, which had been supposed to be one
of a just mediator and a pushing power, with the veto it used in
the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
At the United Nations Friday, the U.S. cast its second veto in
two weeks to kill a security council resolution demanding that
Israel halt work on building 6,500 homes for Jews at Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"A return of the U.S. to the role demanded for it in
the peace process is the guarantee for a return of the peace
process to its natural track after it has actally entered
a big dangerous circle," Boueiz pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that Jerusalem is an integrated part of
Palestine and we consider a control over Jerusalem by Israel
an operation destroying one of the peace process' bases.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz announced that the Jerusalem Committee's conference to
be held in Rabat will focus on this issue and on the ways
to put an end to the Israeli project of building settlements
in Jerusalem and Judaizing this city.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister also called for an Arab
summit "in light of a gravity of the situation and in light
of the significance of what is happening and in light of a
split among the Arab states which has weakened the Arab
position." 
</P>
</TEXT>
