<HEADLINE> Decisive Step Taken in Peace Progress in Angola: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said today "a decisive and concrete step" has been taken in
Angola's peace process as the opposition UNITA promised to send
all its lawmakers and politicians to capital Luanda this week.
</P>
<P>
Annan said at the central city Bailundo he is satisfied with
the commitment by Jonas Savimbi, the leader of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), saying Savimbi has
made the last and critical step toward peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
This time the southern African country will enjoy a lasting
peace and all parties involved should make necessary efforts to
realize it, Annan said after his 45-minute talks with Savimbi
held earlier today.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Savimbi told Annan the rest of the
parliamental members loyal to UNITA will arrive at Luanda Tuesday
and then take office.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA members who will join the government of national
unity and reconciliation is to arrive here Wednesday, said
Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Since the Angolan government has approved to discuss the new
government's administrative program before its creation,
"obstacles hindering the peace process no longer exist," he
claimed.
</P>
<P>
However, Savimbi ruled out any possibilities for himself to
attend the inauguration ceremony of the new government in Luanda
and gave no reasons.
</P>
<P>
Annan, arriving here Saturday, will end his four-day official
visit to Angola on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
