<HEADLINE> Diplomat: Britain Supports Ongoing Proximity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Britain will give its full
support for the ongoing proximity talks conducted by a U.N.
resident representative in Cyprus with leaders of the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot communities, a British diplomat said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides,
British High Commissioner to Cyprus, David Madden, said: "we, and
I'm sure, other countries, are very supportive of this process
and we'll do everything we can to ensure the talks produce
results."
</P>
<P>
Madden, however, declined to comment either on the content of,
or progress in, the indirect talks between President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that U.N. representative Gustave Feissel is
looking into presenting a package of confidence-building measures
to both sides to build a measure of trust between the
long-divided communities.
</P>
<P>
The high commissioner also declined to reveal any details on
the package.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored proximity talks began on March 10, aimed at
breaking the current deadlock and paving the way for a
face-to-face meeting between President Clerides and Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a pessimistic assessment of a Cyprus solution
made in public by the Turkish Cypriot side, Madden said that "I
think what the important thing is what is said in private
and confidentially between U.N. representative Feissel and the
leaders of the two communities."
</P>
<P>
The Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides have agreed to limit
their public comments on the ongoing proximity talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot south and
the Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
