<HEADLINE> Annan Praises Progresses Made in Angola's Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said here today he is "deeply encouraged" by the key progresses
made in removing major obstacles in Angola's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Annan met with Jonas Savimbi, the leader of the opposition
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), in
central Angolan city Bailundo earlier today.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Savimbi pledged that the UNITA will make all
efforts to bring lasting peace into the war-torn Angola and is
ready to send all UNITA lawmakers and members in the future
government of national unity and reconciliation here this week.
</P>
<P>
In response, Annan said the Savimbi's commitment is a major
event in Angola's peace process and will be warmly hailed by the
Angolan people and the international community.
</P>
<P>
Due to the latest development, the southern African country
will regain peace although its peace process has been slow and
mired in difficulties and frustrations, Annan told a special
meeting of the United Committee on Peace Process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
As an African himself, he sincerely hopes Angola can restore
peace and thus facilitate the stability of the whole southern
African region, said Annan.
</P>
<P>
He arrived here Saturday and was scheduled to wind up his
four-day visit on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
