<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister: Cyprus' Economy Shows Favorable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' economic prospects this
year will be much more favorable than those of 1996, based on
encouraging signs from tourism, services and other sectors,
Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Christodoulou said the rate
of growth in 1997 is expected to range between 3 and 3.5 percent
of the gross domestic product (GDP), higher than that of the
European Union, expected to be about 2.5 to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Finance minister noted that his optimism was based on
government measures aimed at improving the island's economy and
on an increasing trend of the general economic indicators.
</P>
<P>
"Prospects for the services sector are much better, while
tourist bookings for this year are expected to be at 1996 levels
with a view for improvement," Christodoulou noted.
</P>
<P>
Commerce, Industry and Tourism Minister Kyriakos Christofi
also said today that despite negative indications at the
beginning of the year, Cyprus's tourism is now experiencing
an upward trend from markets such as Britain, the Scandinavian
countries and Russia.
</P>
<P>
This was the result of an international promotion plan, which
started last year and is still under way, the minister said, but
he did not specify.
</P>
<P>
About two million tourists visit the island every year,
enabling the country to earn around 1.6 billion U.S. dollars. The
tourism sector represents some 21 percent of the gross national
product (GNP).
</P>
<P>
Referring to the manufacturing sector, the Finance minister
said there have been encouraging signs since the incentives and
the financing of export projects started being implemented.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the agricultural sector has been
affected by bad weather conditions, which led to millions of
Cyprus pounds worth of losses.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island, which covers its water
needs to a great extent from annual rainfall, has been hit by a
continuing drought as the water supplies in reservoirs are at
their worst record in the past 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
