<HEADLINE> Turkey Ready to Send Troops to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said today that it
was ready to send troops for any kind of international military
operation in turbulent Albania.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Sermet Atacanli told
a regular press conference that Turkey was deeply concerned
about the grave situation in the Balkan country and would like
to make efforts for the settlement of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We did indicate that Turkey is ready and willing to
participate in any kind of military operation that will be
designed to assist Albania, " Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Turkey took such a stand due to its
traditional friendship with the Albanian people, adding Ankara had
started its humanitarian supplies shippings to Albania.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a high-level diplomatic group led by Foreign
Ministry Undersecretary Onur Oymen arrived in Tirana, capital of
Albania, earlier the same day in an effort to show Turkey's
concern for the developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
After his arrival, Oymen said that Turkey believed that
Albania could solve its problems and the current crisis by
itself, but added that Ankara was ready to participate in any
international effort for the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Oymen carried a letter from Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
to Albania's President Sali Berisha which reportedly called for
calm and reason in the country.
</P>
<P>
A written statement issued by the Foreign Ministry earlier
today said that Turkey had already undertaken diplomatic
initiatives within the framework of international organizations
concerned with the aim of securing peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Turkey signed a military cooperation agreement with Albania
in 1995 and has held several joint military exercises with the
Balkan country under NATO'S Partnership for Peace program.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government has reportedly appealed for police
units from abroad to help secure ports, airports, roads and
railways so that international relief supplies can be distributed
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Following several weeks of political turmoil, Albania, the
poorest country in Europe, came to the brink of a civil war
and also caused serious refugee problem, which aroused grave
concern from the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
