<HEADLINE> German Steelmaker Krupp Gives Up Takeover Attempt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Germany's steel concern Krupp-Hoesch
has completely given up its attempt to take over its larger rival
Thyssen, companies announced today.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued in Duesseldorf, both companies said
the talks between Krupp-Hoesch boss Gerhard Cromme and his Thyssen
counterpart Dieter Vogel are making "good progress" in negotiating
a merger of their steel operations.
</P>
<P>
"Participants agreed that such a fusion would improve the
survivability of Germany as a steel production base and would make
a forward-looking strategy possible," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thyssen spokesman Reiner Hochscheid said that the
cooperation between Thyssen and Krupp will lead to much less job
losses as compared to a takeover.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that due to the larger size of its steel
unit, Thyssen will assume the business leadership of the joint
Krupp-Thyssen steel operations.
</P>
<P>
With an annual steel output of 10.4 million tons, Thyssen is
the largest German steelmaker while Krupp-Hoesch ranked second
with an annual output of 7.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
A merger of the two will create the largest steel group in
Europe and the fifth largest in the world, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
The merger talks between the two companies have been underway
since March 19 after the surprise announcement of Krupp's hostile
takeover bid met strong resistance from Thyssen's management, as
well as mass demonstrations from steelworkers who feared that a
takeover would pose a threat to 10,000 or more jobs.
</P>
<P>
While original protests mainly centered on Krupp, new
development over the weekend saw workers increasingly begin to
pour their anger at the country's two biggest banks, Deutsche Bank
and Dresdner Bank, which have backed the Krupp takeover moves by
piecing together a 15 billion marks (about 13 billion U.S.
dollars) financial package for the bid.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, more than 30,000 steelworkers are expected to hold
a mass rally in the country's banking capital, Frankfurt to
protest at the role played by the two banks. Latest news reports
said that despite Krupp's pullback of the takeover bid, the
protest rally will go as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to Frankfurt because we fear that our future
cannot be helped by the democratically elected government in Bonn
but will instead be decided by the banks," said Georg Bongen,
Thyssen's trade union leader.
</P>
<P>
Despite the failure of the takeover attempt, about 7,000 jobs
are still expected to be lost under the steel merger Krupp and
Thyssen are trying to create this week, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
