<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Eradicate Rinderpest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 24 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan minister today called
for continental cooperation in rinderpest control in order to
increase livestock production, a Kenya News Agency report said
today.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister for Agriculture, Livestock Development and
Marketing Darius Mbela was speaking at the opening of Pan African
Rinderpest Campaign meeting held at Machakos, 70 kilometers south
of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the disease of rinderpest had already
been eradicated in West and Central Africa by 1988 as a result of
the efforts made by the Pan African Rinderpest Campaign.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, the disease is still threatening the
livestock in certain areas in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued recently by the U.N. Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO), last October the disease of
rinderpest was detected in the Nairobi National Park.
</P>
<P>
In November last year, the Kenyan government notified FAO of
the outbreak of rinderpest which was later detected in its
neighboring country of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Kenyan government has carried out a
vaccination campaign against the disease from central Kenya to
districts bordering Tanzania with 1.1 million head of cattle
vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
In 1994/95 Kenya experienced an outbreak of rinderpest which
resulted in a loss of about 50 percent of the buffalo and 80
percent of the kudu population in West Tsavo National Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
