<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends Three-Month Extension of UN Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Annan recommended on Monday a three-month extension, until June
30, of the 92-member U.N. Observer Mission in Liberia (UNOMIL),
which he said should now focus on elections set for May 30.
</P>
<P>
"Whereas much remains to be done and it is essential to remain
alert to the dangers that still persist, the prospects for peace
in Liberia now seems to be more promising than at any time since
the start of the civil war," Annan said in a report to the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"The main focus of UNOMIL must now be the forthcoming
elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
The elections are a key element of a peace accord signed at
Abuja, Nigeria, last August after more than a dozen previous
agreements broke down. More than 150,000 people have been killed
in the civil war, which has devastated Liberia's mining and rubber
economy.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan also appealed for donor countries to
provide assistance to a 10,000-strong peacekeeping force called
ECOMOG fielded by the Economic Community of West African States.
</P>
<P>
He said that ECOMOG is the key to the provision of adequate
security for the elections.  
</P>
