<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-24 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Denies Iraqi Claim on Information About </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait today denied Iraq's
claims that it had provided information about 300 Kuwaiti
detainees in Iraqi jails to the International Commission in
Charge of the Humanitarian Issue.
</P>
<P>
Acting Chairman of the Kuwaiti National Committee for Missing
and POWs Affairs (NCMPA) Ibrahim Majed Al-Shaheen said in a
statement that "out of over 600 files presented by Kuwait
concerning Kuwaiti and third nationals detained by the Iraqis
since the 1990-91 aggression against Kuwait, the Iraqis gave
incomplete replies about no more than 120 files."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi daily Jomhoria said today that "Iraq has offered
information about 300 of 600 missing persons claimed by Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait in the Gulf War."
</P>
<P>
The NCMPA statement noted that replies on the 120 files
included Baghdad's acknowledgment of their arrest and transfer
to Iraq without giving additional details concerning their fate.
</P>
<P>
It said "Kuwait asserts that Iraq is required, from both the
legal and the humanitarian aspects, to provide complete
information concerning the fate of all Kuwaiti, Saudi and third
nationals detained and returned them to their homes and
families."
</P>
<P>
There are 604 Kuwaiti and third country prisoners in Iraq,
according to files prepared by Kuwait. But Iraq denied it had
detained such a number of Kuwaiti prisoners in its
jails. Baghdad gave replies concerning files of 128 Kuwaiti
POWs between February 23, 1994 and February 11, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also returned the remains of one Kuwaiti prisoner last
year.
</P>
<P>
The International Commission formed by representatives from
the United States, Britain, France, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and
Iraq hold meetings on solving the POW problem every other month
interchangeably on each side of the Kuwait-Iraqi border. But so
far no big headway has been made.
</P>
<P>
"As to Iraq's claims of forming an Iraqi National Committee
to search for Kuwaiti and Saudi missing persons, Kuwait would
like to emphasize that it judges results but no claims," the
NCMPA statement said.
</P>
<P>
It added "the only legally and internationally acceptable
result is the release of these prisoners and the end of this
humanitarian problem which is still hanging since the (1990)
Iraqi aggression against Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs is a one of the key problems blocking the
way to improvement of bilateral relations between the two Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Settlement of the issue is one of the conditions set by
Kuwait and the United States for lifting the U.N. sanctions
imposed on Iraq since its August 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
