<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Cases Increase in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of registered new
tuberculosis sufferers reached nearly 20,000 in Mozambique last
year, up 743 from 18,482 in 1995, according to data issued today
by the National Tuberculosis Control Program (PNCT).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the PNCT predicted that the TB cases will continue
to go up this year.
</P>
<P>
The highest 1996 TB-occurrence rate was seen in the northern
Nampula province where 3338 people suffered from the disease.
</P>
<P>
Nampula was followed by the central Sofala province with 3071
TB patients and the southern Maputo province with 2990, according
to the data.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, the south, with 7172 TB victims, was hit most
seriously by the disease. The central region had 7030 TB patients
last year while the north had 5953.
</P>
<P>
The TB cure rate and death rate stood at 69 and 5.4 percent
respectively in 1996 around the southern African country where
16.8 percent of TB patients gave up treatment.
</P>
<P>
The capital city of Maputo enjoyed a 85.4 percent cure rate,
the highest in the country. The TB death rate hit 1.8 percent in
the city.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has to spend more than one million U.S. Dollars on
fighting the TB disease every year.
</P>
<P>
However, the country's fight against TB is much complicated by
its over-concentrated population, its inadequacy of medicine
facilities and experts and the low educational level of patients,
local reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
