<HEADLINE> Doomsday Cult Claims Five Lives in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Three woman and two men found dead
in a house fire at Saint-Casimir, Quebec, were victims of a
suicide pact linked to the Solar Temple cult, police have
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The bodies were uncovered by fire-fighters Saturday evening
after neighbors saw flames coming from the farmhouse at
Saint-Casimir, a village about 50 kilometers southwest of Quebec
City, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Three teenagers were found drugged, but unharmed in a work-shed
on the property. Three of the dead were their parents and
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
Police are hoping that interviews with the teens can help shed
some light on the operations of the cult, which has claimed 74
lives in Europe and Quebec since 1994.
</P>
<P>
No marks of violence were found on the five bodies, which were
not burned by the fire. Police say they do not yet know exact
causes of the death.
</P>
<P>
Autopsies will be performed today and tomorrow in Montreal.
"We'll have to conduct autopsies and toxicology tests before we
know exactly how they died," police was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's incident was almost identical to a 1994 fire in
Morin Heights, north of Montreal, in which the bodies of five
members of the Solar Temple sect were found, according to the
reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
