<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camerounians Urged to Curb TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Minister of Public Health of
Cameroun Titus Edzoa called here today, the World Tuberculosis
(TB) Day, on all Camerounians to fight against the disease, the
number one adult killer in the country.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun observed the day under the theme "the Directly
Observed Treatment Short Course" (DOTS), a strategy developed by
the World Health Organization (WHO) to eradicate the disease.
</P>
<P>
Under the strategy, health workers watch patients swallowing
each dose of the medicine for the first two months of the
treatment and monitoring their progress towards curing.
</P>
<P>
The strategy can reportedly help eliminate all the bacteria at
the source and equally stops the experience of the TB case with
the multi-resistance bacteria.
</P>
<P>
In Cameroun, the number of TB cases increased from about 4,000
in 1987 to 20,000 in 1997, said Edzoa.
</P>
<P>
He said the rise was due to the late detection, especially the
fact that patients do not follow the treatment to the end and are
not well taken care of by the health service.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics from the Ministry of Public Health
showed that only 45 percent of TB patients regularly follow their
treatment until they are cured.
</P>
<P>
Edzoa noted that the ministry has undertaken to intensify the
National TB Control Program.
</P>
<P>
The WHO estimated that TB killed 30 million people this decade
and each year about eight million new TB cases and three million
death caused by TB are recorded worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
