<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian PM Calls for Preservation of Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Bosnian Prime Minister
Haris Silajdzic today called for preservation of Jerusalem as the
spiritual capital of world's three major religions.
</P>
<P>
Silajdzic, emerging from his meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, said Israel has adopted a "wrong" policy on
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The holy city has a special place in the heart of every Muslim
and is considered a spiritual center for Christians and Jews as
well," he said, reiterating the necessity of preserving the
cultural character of Jerusalem as a spiritual capital for all
religions.
</P>
<P>
Silajdzic hailed Egypt's support for the northwestern Balkan
country during its 45-month civil war among the Muslims, Serbs and
Croats, during which 250,000 people were killed and 2 million left
homeless.
</P>
<P>
Saying that Bosnia, with the population of Sunni Muslims
accounting for 43,7 percent, is still facing political challenges
from within. He urged the international community and the major
powers to grasp the real crux of the situation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a mere local or regional issue but an international
affairs one," he added.
</P>
<P>
The civil war had claimed the lives of 200,000 Bosnians and the
Serbs had destroyed more than 1,000 mosques, according to Silajdzic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Silajdzic expressed the hope to cement ties with
Egypt in various domains where Egypt has a rich experience.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will sign three agreements on economic,
scientific and technical cooperation, on encouraging trade and
investments protection, added Silajdzic, who arrived here Monday on
a five-day visit leading a big delegation from the Bosnian Chamber
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili, on his
part, said that negotiations are underway between the two sides to
export Egyptian medicine, raw cotton and other goods to Bosnia,
while the Egyptian construction sector is also participating in
the re-construction program of Bosnia, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
