<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 15:30 GMT March 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain achieved its best trading performance in more
than a decade last year, narrowing the trade deficit on its
balance of payments to 14 million pounds (22.5 million US
dollars), the Office for National Statistics (ONS) announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
has reaffirmed her country's policy towards Kuwait with its acting
Prime Minister and Foreign Affairs Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad
Al-Jaber Al-Sabah. The state-run Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) said
Tuesday, the two senior officials "reviewed relations between the
two friendly countries and reaffirmed its strategic depth (of the
relations)," over a telephone call Monday night.
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- The Hungarian Foreign Ministry said Tuesday last
week's U.S.-Russian summit in Helsinki gave grounds for cautious
optimism. During the summit between Presidents Bill Clinton and
Boris Yeltsin, Russia accepted NATO's eastward expansion in
principle and the talks helped continue, expand and deepen the
dialogue between NATO and Russia, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Gabor
Szentivanyi told the press.
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- China and Myanmar Tuesday signed here an agreement
on border area management and cooperation. Visiting Chinese State
Councilor and Secretary-General of the State Council Luo Gan and
First Secretary of Myanmar State Law and Order Restoration
Council (SLORC) Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt signed the
agreement on behalf of their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Some 600 Belgian, French and U.S. soldiers have
arrived in the Congolese capital Brazzaville to prepare for a
possible evacuation of their nationals living just across the
border in the Zairean capital Kinshasa, newspapers reported here
Tuesday. Thirty Belgian parachutists arrived in Brazzaville, which
lies just on the other side of the Congo river from Kinshasa over
the weekend. French and American soldiers arrived there earlier,
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
