<HEADLINE> Manila, Communist Party Make Headway in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
Philippine Communist Party have made a breakthrough in their
stalled peace talks held in the Netherlands, the official
Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough was achieved after Speaker of the Philippine
House of Representatives Jose de Venecia held one-on-one talks
with top communist leader Jose Sison Monday night in Amsterdam,
capital of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, they signed a historic joint statement which
promised to complete negotiations and sign a final peace agreement
on or before June 30 this year, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first joint statement signed by Sison and a
government mediator in the course of talks aimed at ending the
27-year insurgency by the communist-led National Democratic Front,
according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia, who went to the Netherlands at the invitation of
exiled Philippine Communist leader Sison, reported the
breakthrough in the on-and-off negotiations immediately to
Philippine President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
The exploratory peace talks between the Philippine Communist
Party and the government, which resumed earlier this month, have
been stalled over some humanitarian and human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Communist Party has been opposed to the
government since its creation in the 1970s. Some of the party's
top leaders fled to the Netherlands after its New People's Army
suffered major military setbacks in the early 1990s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
