<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors Raid Nomura Securities for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Agents from the Tokyo prosecutors
office and the Securities Exchange Surveillance Commission (SEC)
raided Nomura Securities Co. and related facilities today in a bid
to find further evidence of shady dealings with corporate
racketeers.
</P>
<P>
About 150 agents from the Tokyo District Public Prosecutors
Office and about 30 SEC agents conducted the multiple search
operation that included the Nomura headquarters, the Tokyo
apartment of former corporate racketeer Ryuichi Koike and the
Yokyoama home of Shinpei Matsuki, one of the two senior Nomura
executives involved in the case, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors office and the SEC launched the search on
suspicion that the leading brokerage house illegally funneld 38
million yen (about 317,000 U.S. dollars) in profits from
discretionary stock deals into the account of a realtor linked to
Koike, the news service said.
</P>
<P>
Nomura Securities announced March 6 that it had found out about
the banned discretionary stock deals sometime in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Two managing directors directly involved in the deals resigned
March 10, while the company's president, Hideo Sakamaki, announced
March 14 that he was stepping down to take the blame.
</P>
<P>
An internal investigation has shown that an account was opened
in the realtor's name in March 1993.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that profits from stock deals made by Nomura
Securities from its own accounts were transfered into the
realtor's account and that documents were falsified to suggest
otherwise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
