<HEADLINE> Chinese Senior Legislator Meets Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- While meeting with visiting US
Vice-President Al Gore today at the Great Hall of the People, a
senior Chinese legislator expressed the hope that Gore will play
an active role in pushing the US Congress to develop Sino-US
relations.
</P>
<P>
Tian Jiyun, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), welcomed Gore and conveyed the
regards of Qiao Shi, Chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, to
the vice-president who is on his first tour to China.
</P>
<P>
Tian explained to Gore, who is president of the US senate,
about the NPC's role in legislation and strengthening China's
socialist democracy and legal system, and briefed him on the
recent Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Tian said that many members of the US Congress have a positive
attitude towards the Sino-US relations, but some lack knowledge
about China.
</P>
<P>
The NPC is willing to enhance exchanges with the US Congress to
promote relations between the two countries and the friendship of
the Chinese and American people, Tian said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Newt Gingrich, Speaker of the US House of
Representatives, will visit China this Thursday at the invitation
of the NPC.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome more US congressmen to visit China so that they
will know more about our country," Tian said.
</P>
<P>
Gore said that he is very interested in Tian's briefing of the
NPC, which has deepened his understanding of the legislative
body. He expressed the hope that the US congress and China's NPC
can continue to enhance their exchanges.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed such exchanges can give a push to the two
countries in learning from each other and deepening mutual
understanding.
</P>
<P>
Also participating in today's meeting were Chen Jinhua,
minister in charge of the State Planning Commission, Liu Huaqiu,
director of the Foreign Affairs Office of the State Council, Li
Daoyu, Chinese Ambassador to the US, and Li Zhaoxing, Chinese
vice-foreign minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
