<HEADLINE> EU Pledges Support for Romanian Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of
European Union's (EU) 15 member countries Monday vowed to support a
financial and political reform plan designed to prepare Romania
for eventual EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The move follows the EU's approval last week of up to 80 million
U.S. dollars in loans to Romania as a token of support for its
ongoing reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Hans van Mierlo, foreign minister
for the Netherlands which currently holds the rotating EU
presidency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Han van den Broek, the EU commissioner for foreign
affairs, said that the EU was "very much satisfied with the reform
programs that have been forwarded by the Romanian government."
</P>
<P>
Romania, which regards its accession to the EU and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) as its top priorities, is
trying to liberalize its economy and attract foreign investment
through a package of reform initiatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
