<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Speed Former Rebels' Integration Into Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Armed Forces of the
Philippines and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MNLF) will
launch a joint information drive to speed the former rebels'
integration into the army, the Philippine News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Yano, deputy chief of state for Operations Office of
the army, today said the information drive aims to educate and
enlighten the army and MNLF forces on the awareness of the
government's peace process.
</P>
<P>
The information campaign has been recommended to Governor Nur
Misuari of the Autonomous Region for Muslim Mindanao and General
Arnulfo Acedera after the army encountered problems in the
implementation of the MNLF integration.
</P>
<P>
Yano said the inadequate information drive on the MNLF
integration into the army and the difficulty in disseminating the
program to MNLF forces in remote areas caused the delay in the
implementation of the integration.
</P>
<P>
While there may be some delay in the initial implementation of
the MNLF integration into the army, he said, the integration
process will continue.
</P>
<P>
In line with the peace agreement forged by the government and
the MNLF last September, a total of 5,750 MNLF members will join
the army. Of the total number, 250 members will be absorbed into
the auxiliary services.
</P>
<P>
As outlined in the plan, the integration of the 5,500 MNLF
members into the army will be completed within a three-year period
starting November 1, 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
