<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Respects and Protects Religious Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- China respects and protects
religious freedom, and this is its fundamental policy in dealing
with religious affairs, the advisor of the Chinese delegation to
the 53rd session of the United Nations Commission on Human Rights
said today.
</P>
<P>
Wang said, "Discrimination and exclusion in political,
economic, cultural and social life based on the belief or
non-belief in religion are not permitted (in China)."
</P>
<P>
He said that in China, a multi-religious country, there are
more than 100 million religious followers who believe in either
Buddhism, Taoism, Islamism, Catholicism or Christianity.
</P>
<P>
There are now over 2,000 religious groups, 200,000 teachers of
various religions, 40 religious institutes and schools, and more
than 70,000 sites of religious activity in the country, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that under China's Constitution, religious groups
are free to independently organize their religious activities and
teachings, publish religious periodicals, print and distribute
religious scriptures, and start religious schools to train young
theological professionals.
</P>
<P>
They are also allowed to conduct friendly exchanges with
foreign religious groups and personnel, attend international
religious conferences and seminars, and organize pilgrimages of
the Chinese Muslims to Mecca, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government protects all religious activities
carried out within the scope of the constitution and law," Wang
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
While enjoying their legal rights, citizens should also fulfill
their obligations which are set down in law, he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "anyone engaging in activities endangering public
security and social order, thus violating others' fundamental
rights, will be punished in accordance with law. This is the
common practice of every modern state with the rule of law and has
nothing to do with whether one holds a religious belief or not,"
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"We all respect human rights, but we should proceed from the
actual conditions of each country to protect human rights,
strengthen exchanges and dialog among various countries and
regions, and avoid arrogance and prejudice," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang added that China is ready to work with the U.N. and other
countries, through efforts to protect religious freedom, to
contribute to world peace, social justice and friendly relations
among peoples of all countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
