<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More than 7,000 Letters Sent to 5th Session of 8th NPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The just closed fifth session of
the eighth National People's Congress had received 7,613 letters
from people of all ethnic groups throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
In many letters people expressed their deep sorrow for the
death of comrade Deng Xiaoping, and said that they would carry out
Deng's will and stick to the reform and opening-up policies under
the leadship of the CPC central committee with Jiang Zemin at the
core.
</P>
<P>
In other letters people showed their good wishes for the return
of Hong Kong and the 15th conference of Communist Party of
China. Xu Guosen from east China's Zhejiang province said in his
letter that on July 1, when Hong Kong will return to the embrace
of the motherland, will be a historical day marking the end of the
100 years of national humiliation.
</P>
<P>
Wei Xinghong from central China's Hubei province in his letter
wished the 15th conference of CPC would keep to the Party's good
traditions and way of doing things, to forge ahead into the future
with one heart and one mind.
</P>
<P>
Still in other letters people gave their comments and advice on
many important issues of common concern. A letter from Deng
Zhibang of south China's Guangdong province, for example, said
that the gap between the rich and the poor in society should be
narrowed as soon as possible, and the anti-corruption drive should
be further enhanced.
</P>
<P>
Many letters were written by farmers. They expressed their wish
for lightening the financial burdens on them and attaching more
importance to the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
According to the Letters and Calls Group of the 5th session of
the 8th NPC, all these letters had been carefully handled, many
had been published on bulletins, and some had been sent to the
related authorities.
</P>
<P>
"We will do our best to play the role of bridge and tie between
the people and the state departments," said an member with the
Letters and Calls Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
