<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Concern Caused by Increasing Automobiles in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The increasing number of
automobiles in Macao has caused a wide-spread concern in the
territory.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics from the Macao Municipal
Council, there are 720,000 motor vehicles running in the streets.
That means about one motor vehicle for every six people in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Local residents and municipal officials said that although the
increase of cars symbolizes a social prosperity, it has caused
negative effects on Macao, which cannot be deleted by prosperity
itself.
</P>
<P>
Traffic jams, noises, exhaust emissions, mushrooming garages in
crowded streets and increasing number of deserted cars have been
among the biggest complaints from local residents.
</P>
<P>
Leong Heng Kau, a member of the Macao Municipal Council, told
local newspaper "Va Kio" that comprehensive measures should be
taken to curb the problems caused by the increase of motors.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that experts discuss issues concerning the
restrictions on the number of new cars, management of parking lots
within buildings, designation of areas for deserted cars, building
of more overpasses, setup of special lanes for buses and special
parking area for motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
"Government departments should pay special attention to the
growing problem of the 'blood vessels of the city,'" he said.
"They should make joint efforts to keep that vessel flowing."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Employers Call for Cuts in Welfare Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 25 (Xinhua) -- German employers today appealed for
a reduction in their social welfare taxes to cut labor costs and
help boost employment.
</P>
<P>
They are demanding a cut in social welfare payments, which
cover pensions, unemployment benefit, health and nursing care,
from 42 percent of average gross salary to 38 percent by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Under German law, employers pay half the amount and employees
pay the other half through deductions from their monthly wage. Now
they say these taxes should be reduced to boost employment.
</P>
<P>
"Those who want to put the jobless back to work must see that
labour costs are reduced and that employment becomes more flexible,"
the Federation of German Employers said in a strategy paper presented
in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
The employers warned Chancellor Helmut Kohl that his goal of
cutting German unemployment by half by 2000 was likely to fail.
</P>
<P>
Official data showed that Germany's unemployment rose to a
post-1930s record of 4.67 million people in February, or 12.2
percent of the work force.
</P>
<P>
The employers also called for a reform of the country's system
which requires companies in the same sector to pay the same amount
of social welfare tax regardless of companies' profit records.
</P>
<P>
They also proposed changing the unemployment benefit system to
encourage people to return to work rather than depend on welfare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
