<HEADLINE> U.S. Reaffirms Policy Towards Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has reaffirmed her country's policy towards Kuwait
with its acting Prime Minister and Foreign Affairs Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) said today, the two
senior officials "reviewed relations between the two friendly
countries and reaffirmed its strategic depth (of the relations),"
over a telephone call Monday night.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed latest international political
developments.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted the contact was made amidst grave
concern from the Arab countries including Kuwait on the Middle
East peace process after Israel, a U.S. key ally in the region,
started the building of a Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem,
which sparked wide and strong opposition from the Arab Islamic
world.
</P>
<P>
Albright also reiterated the U.S. firm policy towards Iraq,
reaffirming that Iraq should fully implement all Security
Council resolutions related to its August 1990 aggression of
Kuwait, KUNA said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. led a western allied military operation in the Gulf
War against Iraq in 1991 to drive Iraqi troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and the U.S. signed a defense cooperation agreement in
1991 under which the latter was committed to the stability and
security of the small Gulf state where the U.S. gets a large part
of its oil imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
