<HEADLINE> Publication of "Global Environment Outlook" Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) and China's State Bureau of Environmental
Protection (SBEP) jointly launched the first publication of the
book "Global Environment Outlook" (GEO) here today.
</P>
<P>
The book, written by experts from famous international
environmental institutions and UN agencies, reflects the current
state of the global environment and its developing trends.
</P>
<P>
The GEO is a biennial series of reports. The book published is
the first issue. The UNEP will submit it to the Special Session of
the United Nations General Assembly held in New York this June for
review.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Kunmin, deputy director of the SBEP, said at the ceremony
that the book raises environmental problems to policy-makers,
urging governments across the world to shoulder their
responsibilities and participate actively in regional and global
environment protection.
</P>
<P>
China will make persistent efforts to improve the environment,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Suvit Yodmani, director and regional representative for the
Regional Office for the Asia and Pacific of UNEP, said that he
hopes that the data and messages contained in the book will be
given serious consideration.
</P>
<P>
The UNEP will strive to do "everything possible" to assist and
support environmental protection and for the quality of life for
generations to come, he added.
</P>
<P>
China, which has participated in formulating the GEO's first
issue and established the China Collaborating Center for GEO, has
made a considerable contributions to the publication of the book.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK World Trade Gap Narrows to 14m Pounds in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Britain achieved its best trading
performance in more than a decade last year, narrowing the trade
deficit on its balance of payments to 14 million pounds (22.5
million US dollars), the Office for National Statistics (ONS)
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
This compares with a deficit of 3.74 billion pounds (6 billion
dollars) in 1995 and was the best trading position since 1985 when
Britain ran a surplus of 2.25 billion pounds (3.6 billion
dollars), the ONS said.
</P>
<P>
Britain's current account balance for the last three months of
1996 showed a surplus of 873 million pounds (1.4 billion
dollars), compared with a deficit of 293 million pounds (471.7
million dollars) in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
The final quarter figures were much better than the 400
million-pound (644 million dollars) deficit analysts had been
expecting.
</P>
<P>
The final quarter improvement was largely helped by a surplus
on trade in services, which rose to 1.94 billion pounds (3.1
billion US dollars) from 1.70 billion pounds (2.7 billion US
dollars) in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
Britain's deficit in visible goods also improved, dropping to
2.58 billion pounds (4.2 billion US dollars) in the fourth quarter
from 2.91 billion pounds (4.7 billion US dollars) in the third.
</P>
<P>
For 1996 as a whole, Britain ran a record 12.2 billion pounds
(19.6 billion US dollars) surplus on trade in invisibles which
includes trade in services such as finance and insurance, as well
as investment income earned by UK companies abroad.
</P>
<P>
The invisible surplus was eight billion pounds (12.9 billion US
dollars) in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Conservative Prime Minister John Major, fighting to win the
general election on May 1, welcomed the figures, saying that
"Britain is booming thanks to people's hard work and Conservative
policies."
</P>
<P>
He said that the world had put its faith in Britain's goods and
services, but added that this success would be put at risk by the
election of a Labor government.
</P>
<P>
The Labor party are well ahead of the Conservatives in the
opinion polls and are favorites to win the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
