<HEADLINE> China to Take Fierce Offensives Against Narcotics Crimes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- China plans to mobilize the whole
of society to launch a series of swift, fierce offensives against
narcotics crimes in the coming years, a top anti-drug official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Breakthroughs must be made within three years in combating
narcotics-related crimes, and with our increasing efforts later
on, the goal of rooting out the drug problem shall be realized,"
said Tao Siju, head of the national leading group of the
anti-narcotics work.
</P>
<P>
Tao, who is also minister of public security, made the
announcement at a national anti-narcotics conference which began
today.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the country has made "remarkable achievements"
in curbing drug-related crimes, "but we still face a serious
situation."
</P>
<P>
He reviewed in the past six years, China uncovered 233,404
narcotics-related crimes -- with the number climbing by an average
of 52.6 percent annually -- seized 324,944 criminals, captured
21,471 kilograms of heroin, 12,606 kgs of opium, 8,491 kgs of
marijuana and 4,374 kgs of "ice."
</P>
<P>
Some 65,066 criminals were arrested, and 49,481 of them were
sentenced to jail, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Tao said, China set up 628 drug-rehabilitation
centers to offer mandatory treatment to 370,000 drug addicts in
the past six years. Eighty-six rehab camps run by the judicial
administrative bodies reformed over 100,000 drug-addicts through
labor during the same period.
</P>
<P>
The scarce planting of opium in some parts of the country
has been promptly eradicated upon discovery, Tao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
