<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Take Fierce Offensives Against Narcotic Crimes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nevertheless, he noted, China still faces many challenges in
the fight against drug-related offenses. They are:
</P>
<P>
-- the invasion of international drug dealers. Total volume of
the worldwide narcotics trade hits more than 500 billion US
dollars a year, accounting for 13 percent of the total size of the
overall world trade volume.
</P>
<P>
The huge benefits and immense consumption market have
stimulated the growth of drug production and trafficking. This has
had an unavoidable influence on China, as the country borders the
world's biggest drug producer to its southwest -- the "golden
triangle" of Myanmar, Thailand and Laos -- which churns out 2,500 to
3,000 tons of opium a year;
</P>
<P>
-- increasing amounts of drug trafficking. Drug trafficking
along the Sino-Myanmar border was reduced for several years as a
result of continued crackdowns, but drug dealers became more
active last year, according to Tao.
</P>
<P>
-- drug addicts are becoming more prevalent. According to the
official figure of 1995, the number of addicts registered with the
government institutions reached 520,000. And today, around 60 to
70 percent of the 5,157 AIDS population in China were initially
infected as a result of drug use.
</P>
<P>
-- more and more drug dealers from overseas are coming to China
to process the country's abundant natural Chinese ephedra into
methamphetamine, or "ice;" and
</P>
<P>
-- practices of opium planting in some places have not been
totally eliminated.
</P>
<P>
As part of the swift and fierce offensives against drug-related
crimes, Tao said a "targeted fight" has been prepared for later
this year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China will continue to enforce its policy of
forced treatment for drug addicts, strengthen crackdowns upon
drug-related crimes and punishment against criminals, improve its
management mechanism on medicines or other materials that could be
used as or to produce drugs, intensify its drug education
campaigns to increase public awareness against the dangers of
narcotics and arouse the public in the fight against drugs,
according to Tao.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 high-ranking anti-drug officials from ministries
and provinces attended the three-day national conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
