<HEADLINE> India's Navigational Aids to Be Replaced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- India's Department of Space
(DOS) planned to help the Airports Authority of India (AAI) to
replace the existing navigational aids with future air
navigational systems (FANS) to ensure better air traffic safety,
Press Trust of India (PTI) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The DOS has plans to introduce payloads in Indian and other
satellites exclusively for this purpose, which would uplink with
the 24 navar satellites positioned around the globe for the global
positioning system.
</P>
<P>
The DOS plans to play a vital role in establishing the
satellite navigation infrastructure to meet national needs
dovetailing into global navigational satellite system.
</P>
<P>
Satellite navigation is expected to replace the inertial
navigation systems in aircraft in advanced countries in the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
The areas DOS has identified for undertaking projects include
signal generation and uplink from navigation land earth station in
the country to two geostationary navar satellites.  
</P>
</TEXT>
