<HEADLINE> HK's ECIC Records 14 Percent Business Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Export Credit
Insurance Corporation (ECIC) announced today a double-digit growth
 in insured business for the financial year ended March 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mr Thomas Yiu, the newly appointed commissioner of ECIC, said
that the growth is likely to reach 14 percent, with total exports
of goods and services insured expected to exceed 20 billion HK
dollars (2.56 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The United States continued to be the largest insured market,
accounting for one-third of the total insured business. The United
 Kingdom and Germany were likely to remain the second and third
largest markets, comprising 17 percent and 11 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
In terms of products insured, textiles and garments formed the
largest group, totaling 5.8 billion HK dollars (747 million US
dollars), or 29 percent, to be followed by toys, and plastic,
metallic and leather goods.
</P>
<P>
However, claims paid out will amount to about 71 million HK
dollars (9.1 million US dollars), rising 57 percent over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
As to corporate strategy for 1997-1998, ECIC hopes to build on
efforts begun in the past year in such areas as consolidating the
marketing efforts targeted at the various services sectors and
product groups, enhancing the computer system and sustaining the
provision of quality service.
</P>
<P>
Challenges such as developing China's inland areas as a
potential insured market will also be addressed by the corporation
which has 30 years' experience in the export credit field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
