<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman on Sino-US Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- China hopes the US will earnestly
abide by and carry out the commitment solemnly made in the three
communiques between China and the US regarding the Taiwan issue, a
spokesman for the Chinese Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions on the Sino-US ties at a press
conference, spokesman Cui Tiankai expressed the hope that the
Taiwan issue would not become an obstacle to the improvement and
growth of the Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
With regard to weapons proliferation, what China concerns most
is the large US sales of advanced weapons to Taiwan, the spokesman
said, "and the US side is clear about China's position on this
matter."
</P>
<P>
As for the impact of the human rights issue on the Sino-US
relations, Cui said differences, which include the one on human
rights, result from different situations in the two countries, and
therefore are "natural."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said China believes "it is not hard to solve its
differences with the US through deepening understanding on the
basis of equality and mutual respect."
</P>
<P>
Cui described the US attitude as "positive and constructive,"
which was demonstrated in Vice-President Al Gore's statement when
he arrived here Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Gore cited an ancient Chinese poem as saying that China and the
US should "scale a greater height" in order to seek more common
interests.  
</P>
