<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Existing Laws to Be Adopted as Laws of HKSAR (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- An signed article released by
Xinhua today expounds on several issues concerning the laws
previously in force in Hong Kong which are to be adopted as laws
of the future Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
It first quoted Article 160 of the Basic Law of the HKSAR,
saying: "Upon the establishment of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, the laws previously in force in Hong Kong
shall be adopted as laws of the region, except for those which the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress declares to
be in contravention of this Law. If any laws are later discovered
to be in contravention of this Law, they shall be amended or cease
to have force in accordance with the procedure as prescribed by
this Law."
</P>
<P>
Based on this, the Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong SAR
of the NPC examined the existing laws on Hong Kong and put forward
suggestions on how to handle them. On February 23, the 24th
Session of the Standing Committee of the NPC made a decision on
this issue.
</P>
<P>
The article explained the following four aspects of this issue:
</P>
<P>
First, the NPC Standing Committee declared that very few laws
previously in force in Hong Kong go against the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The laws previously in force in Hong Kong include the common
law, rules of equity, ordinances, subordinate legislation and
customary law. The Preparatory Committee has placed emphasis on
examining the ordinances and subordinate legislation.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong now has a total of more than 640 chapters in
ordinances and more than 1,160 items of subordinate legislation.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee has decided not to adopt as laws of
the Hong Kong SAR a total of only 24 items, including 14 entire
ordinances and subordinate legislation and 10 items of partial
articles of ordinances and subordinate legislation. These items
account for 1.3 percent of the total number of the ordinances and
subordinate legislation previously in force in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
This means that most of the existing laws in Hong Kong can be
adopted as laws of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Doing this also demonstrates the principle of basically not
changing the laws previously in force in Hong Kong and reflects
the actual need to make essential changes to the existing laws
after Hong Kong becomes a local administrative region of
China. And it conforms to the stipulations on basically not
changing the existing laws as prescribed in the Sino-British Joint
Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong and the Basic Law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Existing Laws to Be Adopted as Laws of HKSAR (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Second, the aboved-mentioned 24 items of law are in
contravention of the Basic Law, so they cannot be adopted as laws
of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
These laws which are in contravention of the Basic Law can be
divided into four categories:
</P>
<P>
-- A small number of ordinances and subordinate legislation
contravene the Basic Law in their entirety; these mainly include
laws reflecting the British colonial rule over Hong Kong and laws
formulated by the British Hong Kong government according to the
Constitutional Bill, which violates the Sino-British Joint
Declaration, as well as the principles in line with the Basic Law
and the understanding and agreements signed between the Chinese
and British governments;
</P>
<P>
-- Partial clauses and articles of ordinances and subordinate
legislature contravene the Basic Law;
</P>
<P>
-- There are some terms and phrases in almost every ordinance
and subordinate legislation which contravene the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Suggestions have been made that those terms and phrases which
are used not in a proper way, but are correct in content, can be
adopted as laws of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it is imperative to stipulate corresponding
principles to replace these terms and phrases in line with the
Basic Law. For example, any government or semi-official
organizations using the word "Royal" in their name should
eliminate the word "Royal" from the name, and then be described as
corresponding organizations of the government of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
-- The British Hong Kong government unilaterally formulated the
Hong Kong Bill of Rights during the transitional period of Hong
Kong. Some special articles and clauses stipulate that the Hong
Kong Bill of Rights has the power to override other laws in Hong
Kong. As a result, the Basic Law will be built on a weak
foundation.
</P>
<P>
These articles and clauses which include the stipulation on
interpreting and applying this ordinance in Clause 3 of Section 2
of Chapter 383, the stipulation regarding the effect on
pre-existing legislation in Section 3, and the stipulation
concerning interpretation of subsequent legislation in Section 4,
cannot be adopted as laws of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
The article noted that the Hong Kong Bill of Rights will be
adopted as laws of the Hong Kong SAR, with the exception of the
above-mentioned clause and sections.
</P>
<P>
This decision will not affect the Hong Kong residents' rights
and freedoms prescribed by the Hong Kong Bill of Rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Stage Gifts and Premium Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is to hold the 12th
Hong Kong Gifts and Houseware Fair and the 7th Hong Kong Premium
Show from April 14 to 17 at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC) said today that
over 1,500 gifts and premium companies will assemble in Hong Kong
to showcase their latest designs at the two shows, Asia's largest
giftware and premium trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
According to the TDC, this year the twin events will be larger
than ever, with the total floor space reaching a record 32,000
sq.m.
</P>
<P>
The TDC expects 32,000 buyers will visit the two events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Existing Laws to Be Adopted as Laws of HKSAR(3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thirdly, the British side had explicitly said that the existing
laws in Hong Kong were in complete compliance with the
international covenants on human rights.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the UN Commission on Human Rights in 1978,
Britain said clearly that the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights was of no legal validity in Hong Kong, and the
obligations set out in the covenant were fulfilled through
different sorts of clauses in various legal systems.
</P>
<P>
These clauses were not formulated for the purpose of fulfiling
the covenant, but they are in complete accordance with it, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
During the negotiations on the Hong Kong issue between China
and Britain, the British side said that there was no need to
formulate a special bill of rights, because the two international
covenants on human rights were both fulfilled through the common
law, the existing ordinances and administrative measures, either
in Britain or in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It also repeatedly claimed that the Hong Kong laws entirely
conform to the covenants.
</P>
<P>
Until 1989, Britain said in a report to the Commission on Human
Rights, that the measures governing procession and assembly in the
Public Order Ordinance and the power of the police in the Police
Force Ordinance were all appropriate.
</P>
<P>
However in 1991, the British side formulated the Hong Kong Bill
of Rights Ordinance, and made a series of significant changes to
the existing laws in Hong Kong according to it, despite opposition
from the Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
None of those laws, revised or abolished by the British Hong
Kong government, contravened the Basic Law, and the British side
in the past claimed that they conformed to the international
covenants on human rights.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-British Joint Declaration has demonstrated in some
provisions that it is the common obligation of both the
governments of China and Britain to retain the existing laws in
Hong Kong basically unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Based on these provisions, the Basic Law prescribed in Article
8 that the existing laws in Hong Kong "shall be maintained, except
for any that contravene this law, and subject to any amendment by
the legislature of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region."
</P>
<P>
The amendments made by the British side go entirely against the
Joint Declaration and the Basic Law. ( More)

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
