<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Existing Laws to Be Adopted as Laws of HKSAR(4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Finally, the amendments of the Society Ordinance and the Public
Order Ordinance made by the British Hong Kong government
unilaterally contravene the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
As the Society Ordinance and the Public Order Ordinance do not
contravene the Basic Law and the international covenants on human
rights, it is unnecessary to make any amendments to them. Even if
necessary, they should be done by the Hong Kong SAR legislature.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bill of Rights Ordinance, the amendments of
the Society Ordinance are mainly: to change the way of registering
a social organization, which will be to inform the relevant
department instead of asking for approval; to abolish restrictions
on the local social organizations to make contacts with overseas
political organizations and also on the establishment of the
political organizations at school; and to abolish much of the
administrative power of the government departments to be in charge
of social organizations.
</P>
<P>
The amendments of the Public Order Ordinance mainly include: to
change the application of assembly, which will be to inform the
relevant departments instead of asking for approval; and to set
restrictions on the power of the police to be in charge of the
procession.
</P>
<P>
It is a misunderstanding that assembly and procession will be
banned if the revised Public Order Ordinance is not adopted,
because the Basic Law grants Hong Kong residents broader and more
concrete rights and freedom than the international covenants on
human rights.
</P>
<P>
As prescribed in Article 27 of the Basic Law, "Hong Kong
residents shall have freedom of speech, of the press and of
publication; freedom of association, of assembly, of procession
and of demonstration; and the right and freedom to form and join
trade unions, and to strike."
</P>
<P>
The original Public Order Ordinance gives the government
departments more power to administer assembly and procession,
which is helpful in maintaining the transportation order and in
guaranteeing the local residents right to live in peace and
contentment.
</P>
<P>
The article points out that there are no absolute rights and
freedoms without limits in the world. The International Covenant
on Civil and Political Rights, on one hand, grants the people
equality in the eyes of the law, the freedom of religious belief,
and freedom and right of expression and assembly.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, it sets out some restrictions in some
provisions. For instance, Article 19 stipulates that everyone
enjoys the freedom of expression, but must respect the rights and
reputation of others, and guarantee the state security and public
order.
</P>
<P>
Any country sets rules for procession and assembly and
restricts rights and freedom of the minority of the people, in
order to guarantee more rights and freedom for the majority.
</P>
<P>
To maintain a stable society requires a sort of balance for any
place, it says. How to establish such a balance should be left for
the future Hong Kong SAR government to decide on its own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0120 </DOCNO>
