<HEADLINE> OAU Ministerial Session Opens to Prepare for Lome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A ministerial session was opened
here today to make preparations for the First Extraordinary
Summit of the Organization of African Unity on the Zairean
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In his welcome address, Foreign Minister Koffi Panou of Togo
said he hopes the meeting will make "concrete contributions" to a
peaceful solution to the Zaire conflict.
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned an appeal made by the president of Togo that
an African intervention force should be set up to monitor a truce
and protect refugees.
</P>
<P>
When opening the ministerial meeting, Ferdinand Oyono, Foreign
Minister of Cameroun who is also chairman of the ministerial
session of the central organ, said the Zaire crisis is a big
challenge facing the whole African continent.
</P>
<P>
The international community is placing "great hope" on the
meeting, and a mechanism must be established to take care of the
problem, he noted in his opening speech.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing meeting is being attended by delegates from 25
African countries, including members of the OAU Central Organ of
the Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution,
African members of the UN Security Council, Zaire and its
neighbors, and some other African countries as observers.
</P>
<P>
The First Extraordinary Session of Heads of State and
Government of the Central Organ of the OAU Mechanism for Conflict
Prevention, Management and Resolution will be held on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources, Zairean rebel leader Lauren
Kabila said today that as soon as negotiations between the two
warring sides of Zaire start, he will declare a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The announcement indicated that he no longer insists on
direction talks with President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
He said he agrees to negotiate with a team of President
Mobutu, but he added that such a team must be fully mandated by
Mobutu and can make decisions.
</P>
<P>
Kabila also stressed that the negotiations will be only once
and must be serious and can lead to a lasting political solution
to the problem.
</P>
<P>
He said that he prefers South Africa to host the negotiations
between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
