<HEADLINE> Bank of China Backs HK Financial Budget for 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong-based Bank of
China has expressed its support for the territory's proposed
financial budget for 1997-98, according to an economic journal
issued by the Bank of China Hong Kong Macao Regional Office.
</P>
<P>
An article of the journal said that the budget was
"appropriate" and it praised the budget's cautious spending,
especially in a year with a huge surplus and reserves.
</P>
<P>
It said the budget was set to maintain financial and social
stability before and after Hong Kong's return to the motherland,
while maintaining ample reserves for the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) government.
</P>
<P>
It said that next year's budget could show a 2.56 billion HK
dollars deficit if there was a change in the way revenue from the
sale of government-owned quarters was treated.
</P>
<P>
It welcomed the decision to spend significant amounts in the
budget on education, housing and social welfare.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that having ample reserves would strengthen the
HKSAR's ability to support the Hong Kong dollar and certain
speculation in the event attacks on the currency.
</P>
<P>
It said that the reserves would also make it easier for the
HKSAR government to balance future budgets, while confronting any
financial difficulty that might occur. 
</P>
