<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from middle east countries:
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Central Bank Governor Gazi Ercel has said
that Turkey would try to reduce its high inflation in effort to
speed up its integration with Europe, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Central Bank-sponsored seminar called "Turkey's
Europeanization Problem in the EU Process" here on Monday, Ercel
said that Turkey should be becoming "Western" before fully
involving itself in the EU, adding this approach was in line with
Turkey's national interests.
</P>
<P>
He explained that to achieve and sustain macroeconomic
stability, Turkey had to take concrete and effective measures to
make its inflation go down to a single digit.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank chief called for a political support for a
medium-term economic stability program needed to reshape Turkey's
role in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We are having currently an exchange of views on this with
concerned departments, and whether this program could be launched
soon entirely depends on whether a political support is available,"
Ercel said.
</P>
<P>
He said the annual inflation rate would be 70 percent by June.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's large-scale drinking water project bidding
has to be extended until March 31 due to unexpected lack of
interest of the tenderers.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today reported that the Manavgat
project near the Mediterranean Sea, which is designed to have a
daily capacity of producing 500,000 cubic meters of water, has
drawn little interest from potential companies.
</P>
<P>
The Manavgat project, which is estimated to cost a total
of 100 million U.S. dollars, was opened to bidding in January
with a deadline of February 14.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's State Water Authority was disappointedly surprised at
the fact that few companies showed interest for this project.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that companies which wish to participate in
the bidding must have a branch operating in the international
market with an annual turnover of at least 10 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The project, which aims to provide drinking water to those
water-deficient countries, will produce an annual turnover of
80-100 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian government has mapped out a strategy on
increasing the economic growth rate to 7.8 percent by 2000 from
the current 4 to 5 percent, said Minister of Economy and
International Cooperation Nawal al-Tatawi.
</P>
<P>
Investment growth rates will also rise by 25 percent instead of
the current 17 percent by the end of the century, Tatawi told the
first session of the fifth conference of Egyptian Expatriate
Businessmen held under the title "Privatization and the Money
Market."
</P>
<P>
Tatawi said the government is keen on encouraging the private
sector to contribute to developing financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Saying that the Egyptian capital market has risen to
international levels in 1996, Tatawi said the volume of
circulation has soared to 11 billion Egyptian pounds (3.24 billion
U.S. dollars) from 8 billion pounds (2.35 billion dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egypt's investor-friendly legislations have yielded
the establishment of 2,400 new companies, said the minister.

