<HEADLINE> PNG Parliament Rejects Motion Calling on PM to Step </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea (PNG)
parliament today voted 58-39 against a motion calling on Prime
Minister Julius Chan to step down for hiring mercenaries.
</P>
<P>
During a four and half hour debate this afternoon, Julius told
parliament that the deal to hire mercenaries was of great benefit
to the country's military, the Australian Associated Press
reported from Port Moresby.
</P>
<P>
He said that for the first time the defense forces would have
had up-to-the-minute equipment and training.
</P>
<P>
He also defended the expenditure, which was reported earlier as
48 million Australian dollars (37.5 million US dollars), saying it
had come from a better than expected budget result in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
While parliament agreed to a commission of inquiry
investigating the government's deal to hire mercenaries, Julius
also said he would appear before the commission.
</P>
<P>
Within minutes of the announcement that MPs had voted to reject
the motion and keep Prime Minister and his deputy Chris Haiveta
and Defense Minister Mathias Ijape in office, violence occurred
outside the parliament house.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that a crowd of more than 1,000 blocked the
gates of the parliament building and others stoned cars at a back
entrance. 
</P>
