<HEADLINE> Developing Sino-US Relations Conducive to World Peace: General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Developing Sino-US relations not
only conforms to the interests of both countries, but is conducive
to world peace and stability, Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of the
Central Military Commission and defense minister, said here today.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with a US scholars delegation led by former US
Assistant Secretary of Defense Joseph S. Nye, he said the further
improvement and advancement of bilateral ties represent a general
trend and there is no reason whatsoever to go in for
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
In developing Sino-US relations, attention should also be paid
to removing interferences, in order to avoid ups and downs, said
Chi, also a state councillor.
</P>
<P>
Nye said he was optimistic about the long-term development of
bilateral relations, because the two countries have many
interests in common.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his readiness to contribute his part to boosting
the development of bilateral relations and increasing mutual
understanding and trust.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they exchanged views on other issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of the General Staff of the
Chinese People's Liberation Army, was present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The delegation has arrived here for academic exchanges as
guests of China's Foundation for International and Strategic
studies.  
