<HEADLINE> Belgian, French, U.S. Troops Arrive in Congo: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Some 600 Belgian, French and
U.S. soldiers have arrived in the Congolese capital Brazzaville to
prepare for a possible evacuation of their nationals living just
across the border in the Zairean capital Kinshasa, newspapers
reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Thirty Belgian parachutists arrived in Brazzaville, which lies
just on the other side of the Congo river from Kinshasa over the
weekend. French and American soldiers arrived there earlier,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The three countries are worried that Kinshasa could soon fall
into the hands of rebels who have been fighting government troops
in southern Zaire since last October. Most foreigners in Zaire
live in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who captured Kisangani, Zaire's third largest city
recently, now reportedly occupy one fifth of the country. 
</P>
