<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Confers with Portuguese Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of
China's Central Military Commission and defense minister,
conferred with his Portuguese counterpart Antonio Vitorino here
today.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also a state councillor, exchanged views with Antonio
Vitorino on the growth of bilateral relations and particularly on
the exchanges between the two armed forces as well as on other
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Chi briefed Vitorino on China's views on the situation in the
Asia-Pacific region and in the world as a whole and the country's
diplomatic and national defence policies.
</P>
<P>
China's defense policy is entirely defensive, he said, adding
that there are a handful of people internationally who have kept
spreading the theory of "China Threat" with an ulterior motive to
drive a wedge between China and its neighboring countries,
undermine China's image and contain the country's development.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all that China has neither invaded any other
countries nor sent a single soldier to station abroad, he noted.
Moreover, he added, China will never take the road of expansion
and aggression in the years ahead and this has already been
written into the Chinese constitution.
</P>
<P>
Chi expressed his satisfaction with the growth of bilateral
relations and the hope that bilateral cooperation, including sound
cooperation on the Macao issue, will continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
Vitorino said the two countries have shared an extensive,
common understanding of maintaining world peace and stability, and
that his country holds that the world has been moving towards
multipolarization after the end of the Cold War, and so peace and
stability worldwide not only require the United Nations to play
its role, but also need cooperation among all governments.
</P>
<P>
Portugal highly appreciates China's major contributions to
safeguarding regional peace and world peace at large and it was
pleased to see Chinese leaders follow the country's reform and
opening-up policy set forth by Deng Xiaoping, Vitorino said.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the talks were Xiong Guangkai, deputy
chief of the General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation
Army, and Portugal's Ambassador Jose Manuel Duarte de Jesus.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Chi presided over a ceremony in honor of
Vitorino, who arrived here Monday for an official visit to China
as his guest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
