<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Feature: Olympians Make Clean Sweep of Top Ten (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- You simply couldn't have
expected bumping into so many sports superstars on one night.
</P>
<P>
Yet sports fans throughout the country somewhat managed to
make it happen, if only in an indirect way, by voting their
version of best athletes in the year of 1996.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, the Chinese Capital Beijing hosted an annual
sports extravaganza of its own, to pay tribute to last year's
outstanding performances in the sporting fields.
</P>
<P>
A space of seven months didn't seem to water down the magic of
Olympic moments. "The Chinese Top Ten Athletes in 1996" has a
full Olympian presence, with ten out of ten basking in last
summer's Olympic triumph.
</P>
<P>
In what might be called the Olympians' night, diving prodigy
Fu Mingxia stole the show from the table tennis phenomenon Deng
Yaping to top the Chinese "Top 10" voting with a virtually
perfect record.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old national sweetheart pulled off a voting
ballots of 261,242, narrowly beating Deng's 260,306 into the
second. The nationwide voting, the 18th edition of its own, has
been echoed by more than 260,000 sports fans around the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is my first time to be selected into the best ten
athletes, and it absolutely thrilled me," said Fu with a toothy
smile.
</P>
<P>
Fu, once the TIME magazine cover figure in 1992, completed the
Mission Impossible at Atlanta by sweeping all of the two women's
diving golds, the first ever diver to do so in 36 years.
</P>
<P>
But Deng's feat haven't at all been shadowed. Having
successfully defended her singles and doubles titles at Atlanta,
the 24-year-old has qualified herself as one of the all-time
greats in Chinese sports history. The girl from the central
China Henan province has now notched up six "Top Ten" trophies,
an equal record shared only by current Chinese national women's
volleyball coach Lang Ping.
</P>
<P>
Yet the veteran wouldn't take it for granted, "Every time I
came here for the Top Ten trophy," Deng said, "I asked myself if
I could repeat it next year."
</P>
<P>
History could repeat itself one more time, if Deng, still the
one with a mission, could remain her typical tigerish style.
"Surely I'll fight on, in this year's Manchester World
Championships and in the National Games also," she confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The athlete who is trying to beat Deng's Top Ten record is Li
Xiaoshuang, the first Chinese male gymnast to clinch the
gymnastics' ultimate honour -- Olympic all-around title.
</P>
<P>
Confined to the wheelchair due to an injury sustained in the
training last month but still managing to take part in the sports
gala, the five-time Top Ten athlete wouldn't wait any longer to
be back to action.
</P>
<P>
"It's really an ill-time injury," Li complained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0143 </DOCNO>
