<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Feature: Olympians Make Clean Sweep of Top Ten (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The long-distance runner Wang Junxia, the fifth-placer in the
votings, is also in the recovery state. The 1993 World Athletic
Championship sensation still feels that her bold move of running
30,000 meters in a short space of eight days at Atlanta was
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
"No other top runners in the entire world would have risked
it," the 1993 Jessy Owens Award owner said, "The gold for the
5,000 meters was a sure thing, yet the 10,000-meter silver was a
windfall blown onto my way. I had thought I couldn't get into
the last eight."
</P>
<P>
Another Top Ten athlete didn't seem that lucky. Compared to
Wang's triumph at her first Olympic attempt, springboard diver
Xiong Ni needed to wait eight years to be standing at top of the
world.
</P>
<P>
However, the narrow loss to Greg Louganis in 1988 Seoul
Olympics and the consolation bronze medal at Barcelona in 1992
only made him a stronger man, Xiong concluded.
</P>
<P>
"All the things I went through in those eight years just
flashed across my mind," the current senior college student
recalled the glorious moment in his third Olympics, "But I
somehow managed not to cry."
</P>
<P>
The entry of the table tennis Olympic titlist Liu Guoliang,
who obtained the same amount of glory as Deng Yaping, only in
men's category, boosted table tennis, an nearly national
institution, to the most elected sports event through the
voting's history, with 14 paddlers being picked up for 26 times.
</P>
<P>
That certainly doesn't mean the contest give a cold shoulder
to less popular sports. Weightlifting world record holder in
men's 70-kg category Zhan Xugang, Judoka Sun Fuming, who won the
first gold medal for China at Atlanta and woman sharpshooter Li
Duihong, winner of the 25m pistol, all came to the party as the
Top Ten newcomers.
</P>
<P>
But Le Jingyi, Olympic champion of the women's 100m freestyle,
is for sure a household name.
</P>
<P>
"Four years later, in Sydney of 2000, you'll see a bunch of
young swimmers in full blossom," Le told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
