<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, US Sign $1.5 Billion Car Joint Venture Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai Automotive Industry
Corporation (SAIC) and the US-based General Motors Corporation
(GM) today signed a contract here to form the Shanghai GM
Co. (SGM), the largest Sino-US joint venture thus far, estimated
to cost 1.57 billion US dollars, in which each party holds half
the stake.
</P>
<P>
John F. Smith, Chairman, President and CEO of GM told the press
that "the United States and Chinese governments have played an
instrumental role in (the establishment of) the joint venture. And
the venture will support the US jobs (market) by generating almost
1.6 billion US dollars in exports for the United States over the
next five years."
</P>
<P>
Located in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai, SGM is to
manufacture '97 Buick sedans, a mid-luxury model, with an eventual
production capacity of 100,000 units. The initial local content
ratio is to reach 40 percent, and will be gradually increased. The
prime target customers are public and corporate users in China.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xianglin, president of SAIC, predicted that the market
demand of deluxe sedans in the year 2000 could hit 120,000 units,
10 percent of the country's car production at that
time. Capacities of Audi and Little Red Flag models, products of
China First Auto Works Corporation, another key local auto maker,
then will reach 30,000 units each.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to meet the remaining market demand after the
first-phase construction which will enable us to turn out 50,000
units, of which six percent are for export," Chen noted.
</P>
<P>
Also signed today was the contract for the creation of Pan Asia
Technical Automotive Center, the first Sino-foreign joint venture
auto development center. According to agreement, the new model
to be produced in the joint venture will be designed by the center.
</P>
<P>
The project is GM's hard-earned result after three years of
"tough competition," according to Smith. Early in 1995, GM and
SAIC signed a basic agreement in Detroit, Michigan.
</P>
<P>
The two sides registered the project in China on September 23,
1996, and China's State Council, or the cabinet, gave the
greenlight in January of this year.
</P>
<P>
Smith cited figures from overseas analysts that even though
China's annual auto production is currently around only 1.5
million units, the figure may hit 2.2 million in 2000, and 3.2
million in 2005.
</P>
<P>
The venture for GM not only provides access to the Chinese
market, but also constitutes part of GM's global network, Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
SAIC plans to take advantage of the opportunity to reach its
goals set for the year 2000. The target of the corporation then is
to register a revenue of 100 billion yuan with a profit of 50
billion yuan, "thus entering into the world's top 500 industrial
corporations," Chen says.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai-Volkswagen Automobile Co., a joint venture clinched
between SAIC and German Volkswagen AG, is now China's largest
passenger car manufacturer. The venture last year turned out
200,000 cars, or 52 percent of China's total.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, SGM then will have an assembly plant, a
stamping plant, a V6 engine plant, an automatic transmission
plant, and relevant marketing and distribution operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
