<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Becomes Top Contributor to Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Agriculture had a tremedous impact on
Nigeria's gross domestic product (GDP) last year with a share of 35.45
percent, a rise of 3.8 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The sector, comprising agricultural crops, livestock, forestry and
fishing, is followed closely by the petroleum and gas sector which
contributed 34.19 percent, according to the latest data of the Federal
Office of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The share of wholesale and retail trade stood at 15.27 percent
while that of manufacturing and other sectors came to 5.8 and 9.29
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's GDP per capita last year increased to
23,491.91 naira (about 294 U.S. dollars) from 20,166.81 naira (about
252 dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
GDP measures the total final output of a nation's economy, which
represents all goods produced and services rendered within a country
by residents and non residents.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural development has been neglected in Nigeria since its
oil boom in the 1970s, resulting in an over-dependence on oil income.
</P>
<P>
Aware of the danger the over-dependence will bring to the national
economy, the Nigerian government has in recent years adopted policies
to encourage the development of the non-oil sector, including
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
To ensure sustainable economic growth and development, the country
has decided to invest more in agriculture this year to promote food
self-sufficiency and increase the income of farmers.
</P>
<P>
In this 1997 budget speech earlier this year, Head of State General
Sani Abacha promised that the government would work out more effective
and efficient mechanism to develop the rural areas, where 70 percent
of Nigerians live.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
