<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng, Al Gore Hold Talks in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng and
visiting US Vice-President Al Gore, who is on his first trip to
China, held talks in the Great Hall of the People here this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Li first welcomed Gore on his first visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
"The Vice-President and I held talks in Copenhagen two years
ago, and I am very happy to meet the Vice-President here today in
Beijing," said the Chinese premier.
</P>
<P>
"Though the Sino-US relationship has witnessed some ups and
downs over the past two years, on the whole, it has been moving
forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier went on to say that China values Gore's
visit and hopes to advance improvement and development of the
Sino-US relations through the American Vice-President's trip.
</P>
<P>
Li emphasized that President Jiang Zemin's scheduled state
visit to the United States later this year and President Bill
Clinton's return visit to China next year are important events in
the history of Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier heralded Gore's visit to China as an
important step in preparation for the coming exchange of visits
for heads of state of both countries.
</P>
<P>
As the 21st century draws nearer, more and more people with
insight have come to better understand the significance of Sino-US
relations, Li said.
</P>
<P>
"The Sino-US relationship in the 21st century will have a
profound impact not only on the people of the United States and
China, but also for the world pattern of the next century," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that the two countries maintaining and
developing a healthy, stable relationship is in keeping with the
fundamental good of the two countries and their people, and is
also conducive to the stability and prosperity of the world and
the Asian-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that the importance of the Sino-US
relationship will be fully reflected in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Li told Gore that China is willing to make concerted efforts
together with the United States, seize the current favorable
opportunities, strengthen dialogue, advance cooperation,
appropriately deal with problems and differences existing in the
two countries' relations, and promote the development of these
relations on the basis of the three Sino-US joint communiques.
</P>
<P>
While emphasizing that the issue of Taiwan has always been the
most important and touchiest central problem facing Sino-US
relations, Li said that China is appreciative of US government
leaders' promise to continue to pursue the "one China" policy and
their commitment to abide by the three Sino-US joint communiques,
which he hopes the United States will carry out in earnest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng, Al Gore Hold Talks in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gore said that he has long been expecting to visit
China. Before this trip, he read a number of books on Chinese
history and culture to improve his understanding of the country.
</P>
<P>
Gore quoted an old Chinese saying to express his willingness to
learn about China's ancient civilization and modernization through
his current visit: "It is better to see once than to hear a
hundred times."
</P>
<P>
Gore said that the US government has always placed great
importance on US-Chinese relations, and the US government wishes
to see China playing an increasingly more important role in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president said the United States believes that whether
or not the two sides can deal with bilateral relations in a
beneficial way, and how the two countries play their roles in the
world will have a tremendous influence over world peace and
prosperity in the 21st century. The United States wishes to
enhance cooperation with China and marches together towards a
peaceful and prosperous 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Gore said that policies mapped out by the US government toward
China were based on this kind of long term-thinking as well as the
strategic interests of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The US government will unswervingly follow these policies and
this will not be interrupted by individual events at any time,
Gore said, adding that his visit to China is the best
demonstration of this pledge.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Clinton is looking forward to Chinese
President Jiang Zemin's visit to the United States and to paying a
return visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Gore paid high tribute to distinct achievements China has made
since it started reform and opening up to the outside world, and
the praiseworthy improvement in people's standard of living.
</P>
<P>
Gore said that the United States supports China's entry into
the World Trade Organization (WTO), as this is in accordance with
the interests of the United States, China and the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
The United States hopes to solve the issue of China's entry
into the WTO through negotiations as soon as possible under
meaningful business conditions -- meaning conditions that are fair
to both sides, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
Li said that as a big developing trade country, China wishes to
join the WTO and has taken great steps to reach the goal,
including making sharp tariff cuts.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to shoulder its responsibilities as well as
enjoy related rights once it enters the WTO, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li said he is confident that China will maintain its rapid and
healthy economic growth no matter when it joins the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier was optimistic about the future of
bilateral economic and trade ties. He said that as China's economy
continues to grow and its door opens wider to the outside world,
the country has provided the US commodities and capital with a
huge market.
</P>
<P>
The recent improvement of Sino-U.S. relations has injected
vitality into economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries, Li noted.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Hong Kong, Li said that China will resume the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Long in less than 100 days. The
return of Hong Kong to the motherland symbolizes that China has
taken an essential step toward its reunification. All of the
Chinese people, including the six million Hong Kong compatriots,
are elated by the good tidings, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's smooth return to the motherland has been decided,"
Li said. "We are confident in Hong Kong's smooth transition as
well as its prosperity and stability. The majority of Hong Kong
compatriots are also confident about Hong Kong's future."
</P>
<P>
Li said that the Chinese government's policy toward Hong Kong,
which is "One country, two systems," "Hong Kong people governing
Hong Kong" and a high-degree of autonomy, is consistent and clear.
</P>
<P>
"The policy will not be changed," the premier reaffirmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
