<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods in N. Mozambique Take Six Tolls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The recent floods in the northern
Nampula province have taken the tolls of six, deluging 15,000
hectares of land and seven schools, the Noticias paper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here today by Silvano Langa, director of the
Department of Prevention and Fight against Natural Calamities
who just returned from on-the-spot survey in Nampula and
neighboring Cabo Delgado province.
</P>
<P>
Langa said 50,000 people were affected, and that they lack
food and medicine and are living in great difficulties.
</P>
<P>
As certain roads and bridges were disrupted, it is very hard
for pupils to go to school, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Besides, drought hit Mocimboa da Praia district in Nampula
province, and peasants need seeds there to sow their land, Langa
said, adding 230 tons of food relief would be sent to the two
provinces soon.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that flooding has hit half a million people in
central Mozambique and one fourth of them need emergency food
aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
