<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia May Sue Investors Unfulfilling Commitments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will take to court those
investors who fail to fulfill their investment commitments
contained in agreements they signed when buying parastatal
companies.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Mail today quoted Valentine Chitalu, the Chief
Executive of the Zambia Privatization Agency (ZPA), as saying
that the investors are liable to court action if they do not
honor such investment pledges.
</P>
<P>
He said the ZPA can ensure a company undertakes its certain
legally-binding pledges.
</P>
<P>
However, Chitalu said most new owners of privatized firms have
been fulfilling their investment pledges.
</P>
<P>
The ZPA can only monitor commitments relating to investments
because they are unable to continue monitoring other commitments
once new owners take over, he added.
</P>
<P>
Last year the ZPA raised more money from the sale of
state-owned enterprises compared to 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1996 economic report of the Ministry of
Finance, 38.7 billion Kwacha (about 30 million U.S. Dollars) was
realized in 1996 compared with 12.5 billion Kwacha in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
