<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Workers Held Hostage in Southwestern Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The security situation worsened on
Monday in Warri, a major oil production base in southwestern
Nigeria's Delta state, as protesting IJaw communities rebuffed
efforts to free the 177 oil workers and traders held hostage.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about nine crude oil flow stations belonging to oil
giants Shell and Chevron have been closed down by the Ijaws, who
began last Saturday their protest against the movement of the
headquarters of the newly-created Warri South local government.
</P>
<P>
The production stations of Shell are located in the Western
Division of its operations in the state, where the company
normally turns out about 450,000 barrels of oil a day.
</P>
<P>
Although oil exports have not been disrupted, Shell has to
suffer a loss of some 100,000 barrels a day while Chevron's loss
is reported to reach about 45,000 barrels daily.
</P>
<P>
The hostages, including 127 Shell workers and 50 traders, are
said to run out of food as the Ijaw communities have been sharing
their limited supplies with them.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, six of the hostages have been
wounded in an abortive escape attempt.
</P>
<P>
Shell's Head of safety (West) Francis Ifedi was quoted as
saying Monday that "Evacuation of our workers (held hostage) have
been difficult as they are confined within the area. Only one of
our supervisors was allowed to reach them."
</P>
<P>
Oil equipment and boats belonging to Chevron and other oil
services companies have been impounded by the protesters.
</P>
<P>
There are reports of shooting in the affected areas by the
protesters using Dane guns to scare off mediators and by the
armed anti-riot policemen. But the news item is yet to be
confirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
