<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Continues Declining in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria now has an inflation rate
of 23 percent, down by five percent from December but six percent
higher than the government's 17 percent projection by the end of
1997, said Finance Minister Chief Anthony Ani.
</P>
<P>
However, hopes are still high as the fall will stimulate
economic growth, raise capacity utilization in industries and
boost purchasing power of Naira, the country's currency, he said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It contrasts with continued depreciation of the value of Naira
at the Autonomous Foreign Exchange Market (AFEM) and on the black
market where 85 to 87 Naira now equal to one U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Press reports today quoted Ani as saying that the fall of the
inflation rate was a result of "prudent" economic policies.
</P>
<P>
These policies include tight fiscal measures to curtail
extra-budgetary spending, the promulgation of the Failed Bank
Decree, the sanitization of the customs, sealing of oil leakages
and harnessing of excess proceeds from sale of petroleum goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
