<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP to Help Zambia Reduce Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) is to spend 24 million U.S. Dollars this year to
help Zambia reduce poverty, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted UNDP assistant resident representative
Michael Soko as saying in a recent interview, ''this is the first
country framework for Zambia aimed at eradicating perpetual
poverty on more than 86 percent of the population.''
</P>
<P>
UNDP and the Zambian government have identified agricultural
development and food security, employment and sustainable
livelihood, good governance, environment and natural resource
management as some of the critical areas to benefit from the
program.
</P>
<P>
The focus will be directed at assisting grass-root levels of
society, particularly the vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
Soko said there is a new world demand to take a keen interest
on environment and natural resource management globally, hence
the need to channel funds in this sector.
</P>
<P>
The report also quoted Zambian Minister of Environment and
Natural Resources William Harrington as disclosing that the
United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) has enlisted Zambia as
a beneficiary for the 75 million U.S. Dollars fund to tackle
environmental problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
