<HEADLINE> Uganda Bans Illicit Anti-AIDS Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Uganda National Drug Authority
(NDA) has put on alert drug inspectors at entry points and
intensified surveillance on a controversial AIDS drug imported
from Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"The authority has never been contacted nor authorized the
importation of such a drug," Deus Mubangisi, the NDA acting
executive secretary, told the New Vision paper.
</P>
<P>
Inspectors of his agency are on duty to ensure that the
desperate public would not be exploited and cheated, he said.
</P>
<P>
A consignment of herirontinasiferon, a purported anti-AIDS
drug, worth one million U.S. Dollars, was imported last week into
Uganda, a report from Zambia's capital Lusaka said.
</P>
<P>
Zambian professor Mulenga Lukwesa, the inventor of the drug,
claimed last week that his patients found his drug is effective.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zambian Health Ministry banned use and sale of
the drug in February until competent international medical
institutions assessed its authenticity.
</P>
<P>
A report from Lusaka said people form queues to obtain the
drug despite the ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
