<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Japan Sign Accord On Rice Supplies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Japan have
concluded an agreement under which Japan will extend a grant
worth 500 million Japanese Yen (about 4.16 million U.S. Dollars)
for the rice supply to the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here on Monday by Peter Ngumbullu,
the Principal Secretary to the Treasury on behalf of the
Tanzanian government and Shintaro Sasaki, Japan's Ambassador to
Tanzania on behalf of the government of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Inking the accord, Sasaki said the consignment will consist of
rice from Japan, Australia, the United States and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He added that the particular food aid grant is extended to
Tanzania at a time when there is a big demand of food caused by
prolonged drought in the country, as well as the recent influx of
refugees from Burundi and Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"My government has decided to make available this food aid
grant to supplement your government's efforts in support of the
people whose food stocks have been reduced due to the failure of
rain and other reasons," Sasaki said.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania was endowed with abundant natural resources
including rivers and lakes which could be utilized for irrigation
purposes.
</P>
<P>
The use of modern farming techniques, such as fertilizer,
agro-chemicals and agro-machinery, also has to be intensified if
reliable food supply is to be achieved in Tanzania, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government has been a supplier of food aid to
Tanzania since 1977 with a total of some 63.8 million Dollars
having been extended to Tanzania so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
