<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Protect Local Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has been
urged to take measures to limit imports of certain products that
have an excessive market share at the expense of local goods.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Mark O'donnel of the Zambia Association of
Manufacturers (ZAM) said that such measures are used by any
government of a developing country if it believes that serious
damage is being done to the economy by unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Mail today quoted him as saying that ''this may
involve imposing quotas on offending products causing the damage
or raising duty levels to a point where those products no longer
enjoy the market access they had in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted him as saying that it is important
for the government to act on his subject without asking the World
Trade Organization (WTO) since such action will be in conformity
with WTO laws.
</P>
<P>
''We can help provide the lists of items that are doing harm
and which require the use of safeguard measures to ensure that
our domestic industry survives,'' said O'donnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
