<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Wants Peace Agreement Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Yasser Arafat, President of the
Palestinian national authority, said today that he was for peace
everywhere in the world and that he was ready to mediate between
the Sri Lankan government and the Tamil rebels who have been
waging a 14-year-old war for a separate state.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who is currently on an official visit here, said at a
press conference held in Colombo today that all he wanted was for
the agreement signed between him and the late Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin at White House, witnessed by America and
Russia, to be honored.
</P>
<P>
If that was done he was certain that peace could be established
in the Middle East as he and Rabin, who later sacrificed his life,
 had believed.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses to that agreement included the European Union,
Norway, Japan, the United Nations, Egypt and Jordan, he said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was followed by resolutions in the United
Nations, and all those who endorsed those resolutions should push
for their implementation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the present Israeli policies were an obstruction to
peace in the Middle East. He was surprised at the Israeli decision
to isolate Jerusalem and construct new settlements both inside and
outside it.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the United States for vetoing twice a United
nations Security Council Resolution demanding that Israel halt the
East Jerusalem settlements. This only helped encourage Israel to
pursue its aggression and its challenge to international
legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government should realize that there is no
alternative to peace. Peace was for the courageous and the brave.
</P>
<P>
"Peace is the need of the Palestinians. Peace is the need of
Israel. Peace is the need of the Middle East. Peace is the need of
 everywhere in the world", Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians were facing difficulties now due to the
closure declared by Israel including their airport, as a result of
which they were losing about 9 million US dollars a day, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Still, he was confident that peace will ultimately triumph.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was thankful to Sri Lanka which had throughout extended
its hand of friendship and support to him personally and to the
people of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that as a person who had seen both war and peace,
he wished the best for the friendly people of Sri Lanka and was
ready to help them achieve it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
