<HEADLINE> EU Team To Inspect Fish Fillet Plant in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A team of experts from the
European Union (EU) is expected to arrive in Tanzania this month
to inspect fish fillet plants in the Lake Victoria Zone, the
local paper Sunday Observer reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reports said some EU members recently imposed a partial
ban on exports of fish fillet from Uganda, as the EU mission had
already inspected 21 fish fillet industries in Uganda,
disqualifying 19 of them from the business.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the 19 fish processing industries in Uganda on
grounds that they were producing fish fillets which were
detrimental to human health had created fear in the EU market,
the reports added.
</P>
<P>
The EU mission would undertake the same task in Kagera, Mara
and Mwanza regions in Tanzania and present its findings to the
relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
Mwanza municipality has eight fish fillet plants so far.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Spain, Greece and Italy had imposed a ban on
imports of fish fillet from Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Spain had conducted laboratory examinations
and found that fish fillet produced in Tanzania, Uganda and Kenya
were a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
Following the ban, Tanzania is losing 2,000 million Tanzania
Shillings (about 3.33 million U.S. Dollars) a month from exports
of 1,250 tons of fish fillet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
