<HEADLINE> Kenya, Eritrea Abolish Visa Requirements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Kenya and Eritrea have signed an
agreement abolishing visa requirements for citizens of the two
countries, the Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
After signing the agreement, Kenyan Foreign Minister Kalonzo
Musyoka said visa abolition would help in boosting bilateral
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that visa abolition was important as it allowed
businessmen from either of the countries to travel freely during
their business undertakings.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Minister stated that the agreement was a follow-up
of the visa abolition announcement by Eritrean President Isaias
Afeworki last May.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean president had noted that the visa requirement was
hindering the bilateral relations between Kenya and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean Ambassador to Kenya Girma Ghebramariam signed the
accord on behalf of his government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
