<HEADLINE> Frenchman Allowed to Scale World Tallest Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 25 (Xinhua) -- French "spiderman" Alain
Robert, who was arrested for climbing the world tallest 88-storey
Petronas Twin Towers here without permission last Thursday, has
been given the greenlight to fulfill his wish.
</P>
<P>
The 34-year-old Frenchman has been allowed to scale the world's
tallest building on April 5 to raise funds for charity, President
of the 4B Youth Movement Mohd Ali Rustam told reporters here today
after meeting the Frenchman.
</P>
<P>
The 4B Youth Movement will bear Alain Robert's expenses in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman, who was released on bail, has agreed that he
will be responsible for the risk he is taking and will receive 10
percent of the money raised, said Mohd Ali, who is the deputy
transport minister.
</P>
<P>
Mohd Ali said the government decided to allow Robert to scale
the 451.9 meter-high tower in appreciation of his ability and
also in the hope that the event would generate publicity for the
twin towers and the nation.
</P>
<P>
Mohd Ali, who is also the president of the World Assembly of
Youth (WAY), said he had proposed that the money raised by the
event be given to the National Heart Foundation, Malaysian AIDS
Foundation and WAY's Micro-Credit Foundation which will be
launched in June.
</P>
<P>
The Attorney-General's Chambers here Monday decided not to
prosecute Robert for last Thursday's illegal climb of the tower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
