<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Ancient Tombs Unearthed in Jiangsu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Two ancient tombs have been
excavated at the foot of a hill in Zhangjiagang city in east
China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
An exquisite jade pendant, a fine ink stone, and a unique
rectangular bronze mirror were found in the tomb of a couple from
the Southern Song Dynasty (1127-1279).
</P>
<P>
According to inscriptions on the tombstone, the tomb's male
occupant, surnamed Qiu, was a minister of the dynasty that once
governed Shaoxing county in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say that the relics from the tomb will
contribute to the study of crafts in the dynasty.
</P>
<P>
The other tomb under the Fenghuang (Phoenix) Hill was for a
couple from the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), which was previously
robbed and now contains only a few pieces of pottery, porcelain,
and coins.  
</P>
</TEXT>
