<HEADLINE> Heat, Lakers Overcome Adversity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The Miami Heat and Los Angles
Lakers were plunged into troubles when their star centers Alonzo
Mourning and Shaquille O'Neal went down with injuries last month.
</P>
<P>
Yet with the return of the centers, the two league powers can
take pride in solid team efforts to vie for their respective
division titles. Currently, Miami, with a slate of 51 wins against
17 losses, leads New York by 2 and a half games in the Atlantic,
while the Lakers, on 45-23, trail Seattle by only three games in
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Out West, the absence of O'Neal who hyperextended left knee and
Robert Horry who sprained left knee, forced coach Del Harris to
rework his entire starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
Elden Campbell moved to center from power forward, while rookie
Travis Knight, veteran Jerome Kersey and fourth-year forward Corie
Blount have rotated in at Campbell's forward slot.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of O'Neal, Campbell has led the team in scoring
in nine games and Blount also put up big numbers, registering
three double-doubles in a four-game stretch.
</P>
<P>
In Miami, Tim Hardaway increased his heavy workload and
improved in every phase of his game. Hardaway who torched
Washington with a Miami season-high 45 points on March 7, has been
the heart of the Heat.
</P>
<P>
Mourning's absence did not stop Miami from establishing a
franchise record for wins, and continuing its league-best 28-8
road record and fourth best scoring defense.
</P>
<P>
Heat players know only a division title will promise that a
meeting against the favored Chicago Bulls won't come until the
Eastern Conference Finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
