<HEADLINE> UN To Enhance Fight Against Drug Trafficking In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations drug
detection units will soon be introduced in Tanzania to enhance
the fight against drug trafficking, a U.N. statement available
here said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations Information Center's
statement, countries which will introduce the United Nations drug
detection units also include four other east and southern African
countries -- Kenya, Uganda, Zambia and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
The five countries will begin training in a US 250,000 Dollars
regional anti-drug detector dog program funded by the United
Nations International Drug Control Program (UNDCP).
</P>
<P>
It further said the select drug enforcement personnel would be
trained as part of the program to handle sniffer dogs which had
been specially trained to detect, through smell, the presence of
specific illegal substances and were used throughout the world in
airports, sea ports, rail depots and at border crossing.
</P>
<P>
The selected officers would receive training in dog handling,
unit command and veterinary procedures.
</P>
<P>
The participating police units will be provided with dogs,
training, kennels, equipment, vehicles and drug detection
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The three-month training course would be conducted in Pretoria
in South Africa at the South African Police Service (SAPS) dog
school. Founded in 1991, the SAPS dog school has established
itself as one of the top such facilities in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
