<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Property Market Consolidates in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian property
market consolidated in 1996 from its robust performance with a
higher value against the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The number of transactions at 270,548 in 1996 showing an
increase of 7.4 percent was higher against 251,546 in 1995 when a
15.8 percent increase was recorded, according to the 1996 Property
Market Report released here today.
</P>
<P>
The value of transactions showed an increase of 22.9 percent in
1996 over a 34.1 percent increase in 1995 but with a higher of
48.99 billion ringgit (about 19.596 billion U.S. dollars) against
39.86 billion ringgit (15.944 billion dollars) in 1995, the
figures in the report showed.
</P>
<P>
Affordably priced houses continued to attract demand throughout
the country in 1996 when houses below 75,000 ringgit (30,000
dollars) formed almost half of the total houses transacted and
those within the price range of 50,000 ringgit (20,000 dollars) to
75,000 ringgit (30,000 dollars) were the most widely transacted in
the country, it said.
</P>
<P>
During the year under review, the residential and agricultural
sectors showed a smaller percentage increase in the total number
of transactions while a drop was seen in the commercial and the
industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
The construction of several large civil-engineering projects
and the acceleration of low and medium cost development in 1996
are expected to sustain the pace of growth, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There was a conspicuous decline in the number of housing units
being constructed, with approvals for construction by the Ministry
of Housing and Local Government dropping by 17.0 percent in 1996
over 1995, it said.
</P>
<P>
Advertising of new housing projects also dropped by 7.5 percent
in the first eight months of the year, reflecting the expected
decline in demand.
</P>
<P>
The report said however, construction of low and medium-cost
houses is expected to accelerate in the coming year due to,
firstly, the participation of the Employees Provident Fund (EPF)
which is expected to expedite the pace of development of such
houses.
</P>
<P>
The EPF provided withdrawals for non low-cost houses amounting
to estimated 665.72 million ringgit (266.288 million dollars)
between January and October 1996 against 535.26 million ringgit
(214.104 million dollars) during the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the Low Cost Housing Fund received a boost with
another 1 billion ringgit (400 million dollars) added to the 3.4
billion ringgit (1.36 billion dollars) to build affordable housing
 shelters for the low-income group.
</P>
<P>
The report said there were suggestions that prices of most
types of houses have continued to rise against a backdrop of a
consolidating market in terms of the number of transactions.
</P>
<P>
There was also an evidence to suggest that while non-housing
construction activities will continue to increase, housing
construction activities may decrease in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
The amount of loans by commercial banks and financial
institutions for building and construction in 1996 grew by 75
percent over 1995, real property sector was up by 20.6 percent but
that of the housing sector bucked the trend, according to figures
supplied by the National Bank.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of 1996, only 598 million ringgit (239.2
million dollars) were released to the housing sector, a drop of 75
percent compared with 2.46 billion ringgit (984 million dollars)
worth of loans released to the housing sector for the same period
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, figures supplied by the Housing Loans Division of
the Ministry of Finance showed the number of housing loans
decreased to 12,464 from 17,700 with amount dropping to 814.27
million ringgit (325.708 million dollars) from 1.12 billion
ringgit (448 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite measures to make it more expensive for foreign
interests to purchase landed property in Malaysia, the total
number of acquisitions of properties by foreign interests
increased slightly to 229 in 1996 from 227 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Foreign interests were keen on investment properties in the
form of commercial, development and industrial properties while
residential units formed less than 10 percent of the total
acquired.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxi Firms Encouraged to Be Merged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- China's big cities are putting
the squeeze on taxi companies by denying them new licences and
encouraging successful fleets to merger, today's "China Dialy"
reported.
</P>
<P>
It's a part of a nationwide drive to improve service for
customers by phasing out the smaller and less reliable operators.
</P>
<P>
Beijing now leads the country in its more than 1,400 taxi
companies and a fleet of 60,000 cabs.
</P>
<P>
Limited by the weak-load highway network which hardly supported
the surge of taxi supply, Beijing stopped approving new taxi
licensces in 1994. That left the small fish taxi firms to be
hunted by the big fish anxious to expand their fleets.
</P>
<P>
Small-sized companies form the mainstay of the city's taxi
fleets. About 1,300 companies own less than 100 vehicles. Some
operators have no more than 20 cabs.
</P>
<P>
The large number of taxi companies -- with small firms forming
the bulk of operators -- meant unavoidable chaos in terms of
service quality and charges, said an official with the Beijing
Municipal Taxi Administration.
</P>
<P>
The momentum of merger and acquisition is encouraged, which is
expected to make taxi mangament more effective, added the official.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now ranks second after Beijing to boast 550 taxi firms
and a fleet of 36,000 cabs.
</P>
<P>
Big taxi companies are advocated to merge with small ones in
accordance with the market rule, according to an official with the
 Shanghai Urban Taxi Administration.
</P>
<P>
And large taxi operators play a key role in the improvement of
service quality because small ones must follow suit to survice,
added the Shanghai official.
</P>
<P>
The northeast coastal city of Dalian tried an alternative
measure in 1992, regulating the minimum fleet of vehicles at 20
cabs then. Dalian's 100 taxi companies are now led by the Blue
Light Taxi Co. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sells 31.15 Billion Yuan in Certificate Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Certificate bonds this year were
met with great enthusiasm from buyers, with almost 31.15 billion
yuan-worth already sold by March 20 -- 25.32 percent of the
scheduled quota.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Finance show that the
three-year bond, with an annual coupon rate of 9.18 percent, was
the favorite of Chinese buyers in the bonds investment craze. Its
sales volume of more than 15.9 billion yuan accounted for more
than 51 percent of the total purchased bonds.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 10.56 billion yuan-worth of two-year bonds
were sold from March 1 through 20, almost 42.3 percent of the
projected issue. Sales of five-year bond have reached 4.657
billion yuan, accounting for 18.63 percent of their scheduled
quota.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China led all the five
designated selling banks with a sales amount of 15.213 billion
yuan. The China Construction Bank came next, with a volume of
6.233 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China has voiced its plan to issue 123 billion yuan in
certificate bonds this year, between March 1 and October 20.
</P>
<P>
China's treasury bonds issue has been growing rapidly in recent
years, to 195 billion yuan-worth last year, and the total amount
is expected to reach more than 250 billion yuan for 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
