<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Resumption of Bilateral Talks Widely Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Both India and Pakistan have
agreed to resume their foreign secretary-level talks, stalled
since January 1994, on March 28-31 for improving their bilateral
ties and this move has been widely welcomed by both countries.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers and prime ministers of the two countries are
also expected to meet for the same purpose in early April and May.
The public opinion of the two countries maintains that the
resumption of Indo-Pakistan bilateral talks is not only in the
interest of the two countries and two peoples, but also conducive
to regional cooperation and development.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, prime ministers of the two countries in their
exchange of letters have expressed their willingness to resume the
talks for improvement of the bilateral relations and this year
their desire has become stronger.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan newly elected Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has said
time and again that he wanted to revive peace talks with India as
"it would be in the interest of both countries." "Through
dialogue, we should resolve our problems and then move towards
prosperity," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his greeting message on February 17 to Nawaz on his
assumption of office as Pakistan's new prime minister, Indian
Prime Minister Deve Gowda said that India was "ready and willing
to have wide ranging comprehensive talks on all issues of mutual
concern."
</P>
<P>
"To commemorate 50 years of the end of colonial rule, the two
great nations and their political leadership should dedicate
themselves to the historic task of correcting the aberrations of
the past and seek to reshape history and press forward in
friendship and cooperation to create a better life for the people
of the neighboring countries," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Since their division in 1947, India and Pakistan have gone to
war three times over the disputes of religion and Kashmir, etc.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the relations between the two countries have
turned sour and tense seriously, hampering economic development of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the two countries have tried to solve their
problems through dialogue at the foreign secretary level, but
failed in January 1994 due to differences over the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Recently with the new global situation emerging and
strengthening of regional economic cooperation, the two countries
have started pursuing economic reforms and opening-up to the
outside world. They have come to realize day by day that economic
cooperation rather than confrontation will not only benefit their
two countries, but also benefit the south Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the platinum jubilee celebrations of the Rashtriya
Indian Military College here on March 13, Indian President S.D.
Sharma urged India and Pakistan to join hands in a spirit of
mutual trust and understanding and work together to fight against
poverty and disease in the subcontinent and for the welfare of the
two peoples.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the Institute of Strategic Studies in
Islamabad on March 16, Pakistan Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan
said that India and Pakistan had "both realized the importance of
bilateral discussions if they are to witness a stable future."
</P>
<P>
"Has anybody sat down in India or Pakistan to calculate how
much they have spent on defense from 1948 and how long we continue
doing this?" He asked. "We can compete, India and Pakistan, on an
economic front," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion is building up in both countries for
normalization of relations. Holding its third session recently in
India's Calcutta since 1994, the Pakistan-India People's Forum for
Peace and Democracy called upon the two governments to sign a
comprehensive treaty by August 15 this year for lasting peace in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The declaration of the meeting participated by leading citizens
of the two countries urged the two governments to begin working to
realize the aspirations of the peoples.
</P>
<P>
Renunciation of force and cessation of all forms of proxy wars
had been unequivocally demanded. Free trade and travel across
borders, unhindered flow of information and publications, lowering
of the cost of communication and mutual "Favored Nation" treatment
had been suggested.
</P>
<P>
While cultural personalities, political leaders and social
activists have raised their voice; Businessmen, industrialists and
traders have also called for regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
That a new wind is blowing across the border is an evident in
the exchange of letters between school children of Mumbai (Bombay)
and Karachi, two biggest port cities of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A school boy from Karachi recently wrote to his pen-friend in
Mumbai: "I am writing this letter to establish good and cordial
relations between us. In this way most of our fights and disputes
will be over." In response, his Indian friend shared his views.
</P>
</TEXT>
