<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Change Tariff, Taxation Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will introduce radical
changes in its tariff and taxation systems this week by lowering
down import tariff to 45 percent and levying agricultural tax,
local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
General sales tax will be reduced to 15 percent and income tax
will also be cut down.
</P>
<P>
All non-essential public services, most of which are provided
by the public sector corporations, will be zero-budgeted. This
means that the government will not provide any budget to these
corporations to make up deficit.
</P>
<P>
An ordinance of agricultural income tax, promulgated by the
caretaker government, is also being converted into an act.
</P>
<P>
The changes, which will be given last toughs at a meeting in
the Finance Ministry today, is likely to be announced on Wednesday
by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
After the successful implementation of the said economic relief
package, the government is expected to start its negotiations with
the International Monetary Fund for a long-term low-interest
Extended Structural Adjustment Facility before the forthcoming
budget in June this year, according to the reports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
