<HEADLINE> Thailand's Export Growth Target Endorsed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Economic Affairs
Screening Committee Monday endorsed an official export target of
1,550 billion baht (62 billion U.S. dollars) for 1997,
representing a growth of 10 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
The committee rejected as unrealistic a Commerce Ministry
target of 1,620 billion baht (64.8 billion dollars), or 15 percent
growth, according to Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay Virawan.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's export was only 0.4 percent higher
than the year before.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's export is expected to improve this year as a result
of expected higher world economic growth and higher world trade.
</P>
<P>
Improved export prospects are seen in important markets
including ASEAN, the United States, Japan and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
To remove export obstacles to exporters, the Thai government
has promised to help boost export by speeding up value-added tax
refunds.
</P>
<P>
Among the more promising sectors are electrical appliances,
electronic goods, jewelry, automobiles and parts, canned seafood,
canned fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN will remain the top export market, with a forecast of
an 11.7 percent increase. Exports to the EU are forecast to grow
by 10.6 percent, to Japan up 10 percent and the U.S. up 9.8
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
