<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-French Economic Cooperation on Steady Rise (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Since the governments of China and
France in a joint communique in January 1994 declared the full
normalization of bilateral ties, a new page has been turned in the
development of relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the active support of the leaders and the joint
efforts of the economic and entrepreneurial circles of China and
France, the economic and trade relations between the two countries
have entered a period of steady rise and vigorous development.
</P>
<P>
The political relationship between China and France is the
driving force behind their economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
The visit paid to France by Chinese President Jiang Zemin in
September 1994 and that to China by former French Prime Minister
Edouard Balladur in April 1994 signaled the return of Sino-French
relations to the track of normal development.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations were further developed by the successful
visit to France by Chinese Premier Li Peng in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the foreign ministers of the two countries have made
a number of visits to each other's country and held talks on
several occasions to exchange views on issues of common interest
and to coordinate their respective positions.
</P>
<P>
They reached identical or similar views on many important
international issues in those talks.
</P>
<P>
All these high-level visits and political consultations have
strongly pushed forward the development of lasting, steady and
friendly relations between China and France, and have laid a firm
basis for economic cooperation of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Both China and France are nations of strong influence in the
world, and cooperation between the two in economic fields have a
wide-range basis.
</P>
<P>
France is the world's fourth biggest exporting nation and the
third largest nation of investments.
</P>
<P>
China's economy is experiencing a speedy, lasting and sound
development and the country represents a huge potential market.
So, China and France have a wide perspective for carrying out
cooperation in economic and trade fields.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics provided by the Customs of
China, the trade between the two countries has been keeping a
momentum of growth over the past two years, with bilateral trade
attaining 4.49 billion U.S. dollars in 1995 -- which was 33.5
percent more than 1994 -- and 4.15 billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, France has been active in making investments in
China. In the first nine months of 1996, French businesses signed
a total of 146 contracts with their Chinese counterparts, which
were estimated at 244 million dollars and represented a 79-percent
increase over the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
French funded projects in China now amount to about 1,103 with
an estimated value of 1.3 billion dollars. The fields these
projects cover include automobiles, electronics, brewery, and
plastic materials.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng's official visit to France last year further
promote the economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-French Economic Cooperation on Steady Rise (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During Premier Li's visit, China and France signed a number of
economic and trade cooperation agreements which amounted up to 2.4
billion dollars, including the purchase by China of 33 Airbus
passenger aircraft.
</P>
<P>
France owns and produces the world's most advanced technologies
and products in the fields of agriculture, energy, aeronautics,
airspace industry, transportation, telecommunications and
chemistry. All these are among the fields for priority
development in China.
</P>
<P>
China and France are now beginning to realize a joint project
of developing 100-seat passenger aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, France's small and medium-sized enterprises are also
tapping the Chinese market for cooperation in food processing and
garment production.
</P>
<P>
Although Sino-French economic and trade cooperation have
greatly developed, such cooperation still have great potentials
because of the economic power of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to French official statistics, bilateral trade volume
between China and France only accounts for 1.7 percent of China's
overall overseas trade volume.
</P>
<P>
France is ranked China's 11th trade partner, behind Germany and
Italy, while its investment in China is also smaller than those of
Germany and Britain.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day France-China economic seminar held in
Beijing last week, French business and trade representatives led
by former Prime Minister Raymond Barre discussed with their
Chinese counterparts ways to strengthen and further economic and
trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The President of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress of China, Qiao Shi, will begin a visit in France
on Tuesday. And French President Jacques Chirac will pay a state
visit to China in May.
</P>
<P>
The two visits are expected to strongly push forward the
relations of comprehensive cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
