<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dini of Italy Calls for Furthering European Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The journey toward European
integration must not stop now, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini said on the eve of the 40th anniversary of the Treaty of Rome.
</P>
<P>
The treaty of Italy, France, West Germany, the Netherlands,
Belgium and Luxembourg created the European Economic Community
that later was turned into the 12-member European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Through the years after the signing of the document on March
25, 1957, by the six countries, "history has taught us that the
journey toward European integration must not stop," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for a permanent renewal...if we want to be up
to the task of meeting new challenges," Dini wrote in the preface
to a dossier titled "40 Years of Europe: An Agenda for the Union".
</P>
<P>
He discussed, in the booklet prepared by the official ANSA news
agency, about what the ongoing EU integration could bring along --
a single market and currency, institutional reform, and others.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers will meet here on Tuesday to mark the
treaty's anniversary and attend a session of the intergovernmental
conference to revise the Maastricht Treaty on European Union.
</P>
<P>
The session is key to a "common European security and foreign
policy to restore the EU's legitimacy and to dispel skepticism,"
Dini and his French counterpart Herve de Charette said in a joint
article in today's French newspaper Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
"The Albanian crisis has shown how much of our journey toward
European integration still remains if the EU wants to impose
itself with authority on the international scene and to achieve a
truly united security and foreign policy," the two ministers said.
</P>
<P>
They also called for finding an "authoritative person" to
handle the EU's foreign policy, introducing majority voting in the
decision-making process of the EU Council of Ministers, and fully
integrating the Western European Union, the European military
alliance, into the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
