<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Klestil: EU Develops Into Real Important Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Austrian President Thomas Klestil
said today that the European Union (EU) had developed into a
really important community, and the core guarantor of security and
stability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a news release on the eve of the 40th
anniversary of the Treaty of Rome. This historic pact was signed
in Rome, Italy on March 25, 1957 between West Germany, France,
Italy, the Netherlands, Belgium and Luxembourg to forge peace and
create a common market in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The result of the treaty was the establishment of the European
Economic Community which is now the EU, which ranges from Ireland
to Greece and Finland to Spain.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian president said Europe's unification had not been
geographically or "substantially achieved yet".
</P>
<P>
"The common worry that Europeans now have about employment,
social and environmental problems as well as internal and external
security becomes quite urgent," Klestil said.
</P>
<P>
The European continent is much larger than the 15-nation bloc,
Klestil said, urging that more efforts must be made not only for
European residents, but also with them to jointly build Europe.
</P>
<P>
Klestil stressed that "the longest peaceful period in the
European history" resulted from unification above all. For every
European, to do a bit more now for the unification would mean a
step forward toward more peace, security and prosperity in the
future.
</P>
<P>
He said Austrians, who once suffered with other Europeans from
decades of divisions in Europe, were especially concerned about
unification in the entire continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
