<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Albania Agree on Naval Patrols in Adriatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Italy and Albania agreed today on
arrangements for naval patrols in the Adriatic Sea to stop the
flow of refugees and illegal immigrants to southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came during a meeting between Italian Prime
Minister Romano Prodi and his visiting Albanian counterpart
Bakshim Fino.
</P>
<P>
Since the breakdown in law and order in Albania precipitated
the crisis there earlier this month, around 12,000 Albanians have
taken refuge in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Initially, the Albanians coming to Italy were considered
genuine refugees. But the authorities in Italian port city of
Brindisi said today the Albanians now arriving were illegal
immigrants who came from areas without disturbances.
</P>
<P>
Their transport, often on rusty and leaking crafts, was
arranged by criminal gangs who were making money from the crisis,
Italian officials said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 570 Albanians arrived in Brindisi
today, but the local Prefect ordered the arrest of all the crews
and the seizure of all boats bringing people across the sea.
</P>
<P>
"Controlling the Adriatic will mean stemming the flow of the
illegal immigrants," Prodi told reporters after meeting with Fino.
</P>
<P>
Fino said, "The two governments will collaborate on the problem
of emigration. The time has come for this problem to be tackled
in a more decisive manner."
</P>
<P>
The agreement on naval patrols came after the European Union
(EU) foreign ministers in Brussels agreed on sending humanitarian
aid to Albania with escort.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said Italy had been
asked to lead the escort force, which would also include French,
Spanish and Portuguese units.
</P>
<P>
Hans van Mierlo, the deputy Dutch president of the Council of
Ministers, said the humanitarian aid valued at 2 million ECU
(about 2.3 million U.S. dollars) would be sent to Albania in the
first instance.
</P>
<P>
It could be followed by further shipments after a consultative
mission to Albania submitted a report, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted the mandate of the protection force would
be a limited mission, defined by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Italy has been assembling troops and equipment in Brindisi in
anticipation of an EU decision to send a force to protect food-aid
shipments to Albania.
</P>
<P>
The EU ministers will meet again in Rome on Tuesday, and Fino
will also attend the meeting to discuss Albania's problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
