<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: EU Reaches Turning Point After 40 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 25 (Xinhua) -- After 40 years, the European
Union (EU) is finding itself confronted with the most difficult
choice it has ever been compelled to make: to run the risk of
moving forward with its integration plan or to stay calm and think
about it for a while.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of EU's 15 member countries were scheduled to
meet Tuesday in Rome to mark the signing on March 25, 1957, of the
Treaty of Rome. The pact created a common market among West
Germany, France, Italy, the Netherlands, Belgium and Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The European Economic Community (EEC) was established by the
pact. Once comprising what the European Union is now, it has been
enlarged to 15 member states -- and a dozen countries are waiting
at its doorstep.
</P>
<P>
Even Russia, which is firmly opposed to NATO expansion toward
its borders, has expressed interest in joining in.
</P>
<P>
The idealistic experiment in cooperation among governments,
which was conducted by the founding fathers of European
integration, has so far achieved its original goal of binding the
continent's economies closely together and making war unthinkable
among countries of western Europe.
</P>
<P>
The EU is making every effort to realize its most ambitious
dream: Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) by January 1, 1999. But
it is far from being satisfied with the present extension of
integration, insisting on the Treaty of Rome's fundamental goal of
an "ever closer union".
</P>
<P>
Some skeptics say this would be too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
Integration in sensitive areas, such as a common currency and
border controls, has prompted a nationalist backlash while
expansion from the six original members to the current 15 -- and
even to a dozen more -- has frayed consensus over policy
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Faced with the issue of mass unemployment, people across the
continent -- including Britons who have long been at odds with
the EU over its integration plan -- are beginning to cast doubts
over the efficiency of a common market in providing solutions.
</P>
<P>
The EU seemed to be paralyzed when Renault workers took to the
streets to protest the abrupt closure of an auto plant in Belgium,
an incident that has posed a big challenge to the EU's dream of
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Few politicians on the continent would question the rationale
of integration at a time when economic globalization prevails in
the world. But welfare systems and labor rules remain in the
hands of national governments of EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Wim Kok, Dutch prime minister and EU president who is leading
talks on EU reform, said: "In my view, there is no alternative to
the further development of integration."
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, confronted with
the thorny issue of a record jobless rate at home and the
possibility of seeing a weaker Euro after the inclusion of the
Italian lira and the Spanish peseta, argued that European
integration was a question of peace or war.
</P>
<P>
Under a common market, some richer countries must sacrifice
themselves somewhat in order to be fair to other nations -- not to
mention other problems integration could cause.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, financial markets in Europe -- though admitting
there is political will behind the EMU -- have come to see the
necessity of a delay in launching the single currency until more
countries are ready.
</P>
<P>
Equally fortunate, Europeans have realized there are problems
with the integration plan and they are beginning to do something
about these problems. The budget-cutting reforms being undertaken
on behalf of monetary union will strengthen Europe's capacity to
grow and create jobs, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
The choice remains a difficult one. Meanwhile, as Wim Kok
said, tensions and doubts reflect the far-reaching nature of
imminent decisions on a single currency and constitutional reforms
which will shape Europe into the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Government Cuts Down Facilities for Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
decided to slash the housing facilities for ministers with the
objective of checking unnecessary public expenditure, according to
the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The government has cut down the housing allowance of 200,000
rupees (over 3,500 US dollars) for each cabinet member to 50,000
rupees (less than 900 dollars), the ministry said in a press
communique Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the government, which just took
power nearly two weeks ago, will reduce the number of foreign
visits by Nepali individuals and delegations at the expenses of
the government.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements will be made for representatives from Nepali
Embassies abroad to take part international meetings in foreign
countries and only small delegations will be sent abroad if it is
found necessary to send such delegations to important conferences
on behalf of the country, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to keep medical spending under a
desired limit and provide medical subsidies only to personalities
of national importance, it added.
</P>
<P>
In his statement of the government's policy program last week,
Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand pledged to reduce
administrative expenditure and facilities for ministers under the
principle of austerity.  
</P>
