<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq to Receive Food, Medicine Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq is soon to receive
its much needed food and medicine in exchange for the oil it has
pumped out since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
So far 57 related contracts have been approved and more
applications have been submitted, according to Portugal's Antonio
Monteiro, who is chairing the United Nations Security Council
committee concerning the situation between Iraq and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese ambassador to the United Nations told a press
briefing today after a closed-door meeting on the issue: "We have
the agreement on priorities."
</P>
<P>
He said: "We have to go further to look at some specific
issues."
</P>
<P>
An official from the Iraqi mission to the U.N. told the press
that about 1 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil has been exported
by different Iraqi companies since January. He expected food and
medicine start arriving in Iraq early next month.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate transportation, Jordan had applied to fly regular
flights into Iraq, hopefully once a week.
</P>
<P>
Monteiro said Turkish companies were trying to supply some
equipment and pipe lines to speed the transportation of oil.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iraqi official, Iraq was going to complete the
export of another 1 billion dollars worth of oil during the next
three months.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. resolution 986, Iraq is allowed to sell oil
worth 2 billion dollars in exchange for food and medicine over a
period of six months. And 30 percent of the income should be used
to compensate victims of the Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
