<HEADLINE> Ramos Waits for Congress' Decision on Marcos Burial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
has said it should be Congress who decides whether or not to bury
the remains of former president Ferdinand Marcos at a heroes'
cemetery in the country, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"This resolution will have to go through both houses (of
Congress) if it is to be acted upon by the president. Let us await
the action of the entire Congress," Ramos was quoted as saying
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the House of Representatives approved a resolution
urging Ramos to allow the burial of the late strongman at the
Libingan Ng Maga Bayani, a cemetery reserved for government
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Marcos' body remains refrigerated in a crypt at the family
mansion in Batac city in northern Luzon.
</P>
<P>
Press Undersecretary Marcelo Lagmay said Ramos may form a
cabinet cluster on the issue of Marcos burial after a joint
House-Senate resolution is passed.
</P>
<P>
Marcos had ruled the Philippines with an iron hand from 1972 to
1986 before he was finally ousted in a popular rebellion led by
his police chief and defense minister. He fled to the United
States after the rebellion and died there in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, a local power company cut off power supply
to Marcos' crypt after Marcos' widow Emelda failed to pay millions
of pesos of overdue power rates.
</P>
<P>
Emelda then asked Ramos to let Marcos be buried in the heroes'
cemetery as the late president wished in his will.
</P>
<P>
According to Emelda, Ramos had promised to let Marcos rest in
the heroes' cemetery in 1992 in exchange for Emelda's support for
his bid to run for president. But Ramos denied making such a
promise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
