<HEADLINE> Air Assistance Reaches Albania as Life Returns to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- An assistance plane and a
commercial flight landed in this capital city of Albania on Monday
as the country began to return to normal after weeks of anarchy.
</P>
<P>
An Italian Hercules air-force transport plane landed at Rinas
International Airport in Tirana with six tonnes of emergency
medical aid requested by Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino for
the northern part of the country, which is under government
control.
</P>
<P>
Italy has already sent two tonnes of medical aid for the south.
</P>
<P>
The cargo arrived at the airport shortly before an Austrian
Airlines jet landed -- the first Western commercial flight to
arrive there since the airport was closed 11 days ago.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled flights from Switzerland and Germany are expected on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Albania's largest port of Durres in the north,
some 40 kilometers west of Tirana, reopened as shipping cargo of
thousands of tonnes of wheat flour arrived.
</P>
<P>
Albania's key roads running from Tirana to other countries were
to reopen this week.
</P>
<P>
Passenger traffic between Tirana and Macedonia's capital of
Skopje, as well as Turkey's largest city of Istanbul, were also
scheduled to resume this week, government sources said.
</P>
<P>
The reopen of airport, ports and roads are visible signs that
life is returning to normal in Albania, where order has broken
down in wide areas in the south after an armed revolt erupted this
month.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Fino flew to Rome for talks on how Europe can bring
aid to Albania and help it restore order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
