<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- The General Offices of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
Central Committee and the State Council have issued a set of
regulations on leading officials reporting important personal
matters to relevant departments.
</P>
<P>
The matters that are required to be reported include personal
housing, housing trading or leasing by themselves, their spouse or
children living with them; their weddings or weddings and funerals
of their close relatives handled by the officials themselves;
their own marriages or their childrens' marriages with foreigners,
and their spouse or children's traveling and residing overseas;
and their traveling overseas for private reasons and their
activities during their overseas stay.
</P>
<P>
-- A front-page editorial considered the regulations an
essential measure taken by the CPC to strengthen the management
and supervision over the leading officials and advance the
building of a cleaner government.
</P>
<P>
It quoted CPC Central Committee General Secretary Jiang Zemin
as saying that a ruling party would have to face a dreadful future
if it could not well manage its leading officials.
</P>
<P>
The editorial asked officials at all levels to study the
regulations and map out specific rules to carry them out.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- A total of 100 urban areas and 200 towns and villages have
been selected to be pilot zones to promote cultural and ethical
progress.
</P>
<P>
The namelist was announced by the Propaganda Department of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee at a telephone
conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot zones cover all the Chinese provinces, municipalities,
and autonomous regions. On the basis of improving cultural and
ethical progress in these pilot urban and rural areas, and work
units, the overall quality of China's cities, towns, villages, and
work units are expected to be greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
-- US Vice-President Albert Gore arrived in Beijing from Tokyo
Monday evening on a five-day official visit to China at the
invitation of Chinese Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
This is Gore's first trip to China since he took office on
January 20, 1993. The vice-president is the highest-ranking US
official to visit China since the beginning of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement released upon his arrival at the
airport, Gore said, "I've traveled here to reaffirm the vital
importance of relations between our nations, and to continue
building a lasting peace between China and the United States,"
said the vice-president.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Early talks across the Taiwan Straits have been ruled
out by an official of a Beijing-based association working for
peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
Officials on the island, and its so-called "president", Lee
Tung-hui, will first have to abandon their splittist activities
before dialogue can begin, said Tang Shubei, vice-chairman of the
Association fro Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (Arats).
</P>
<P>
Tang believed that the success of Hong Kong's return to the
motherland will provide an enlightening example for the settlement
of the Taiwan issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
