<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Calls on Soldiers to Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Albania's Defense Ministry today
appealed to the servicemen to return to their barracks as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The ministry called on all soldiers who were serving in the
army, and who had left temporarily, to return to their barracks to
protect Albania's freedom, independence and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
"Albania is in an unusual situation and your motherland is
waiting for you," the Defense Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that most compulsory servicemen among Albania's
45,000-strong troops deserted their posts when anti-government
protesters began raiding armories and barracks for weapons earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
Violence erupted in southern Albania in January over the
collapse of high-risk government investment schemes, in which
thousands of Albanian families lost money.
</P>
<P>
The situation worsened earlier this month after violence
escalated into armed conflicts and spread to most parts of the
Balkan country. More than 100 people were killed and 12,000
Albanians fled Italy.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, which turned down an Albanian request for
large-scale military intervention to help restore order, has
decided to send a team of two dozen civilian and military experts
there to give advice on rebuilding the country's disintegrating
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The union also agreed to provide the nation with immediate food
and medical aid worth two million ecus (about 2.3 million
U.S. dollars), most of which is earmarked for orphanages, old-age
homes and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Restoring order is seen as the top priority for the newly
established Albanian government for national reconciliation. But
armed protesters in the south have refused to surrender their
weapons unless President Sali Berisha, who is blamed for the
failed investment schemes, resigns.
</P>
<P>
However, Berisha refused to resign and said he would step down
only if his Democratic Party lost the forthcoming general
elections in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
