<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Consumes Less Gasoline in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Gasoline consumption in
Venezuela's automobile sector decreased by 7 percent, or 14,000
barrels per day, to an average of 183,000 barrels per day in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The lower gasoline consumption, relative to 1995, was in line
with a 6-percent drop in the sales of liquid fuels in the country,
the state-owned petroleum company PDVSA said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
While the year saw the sales of liquid fuels decreasing to
354,000 barrels per day, the daily sales of natural gas increased
by 6 percent to an equivalent of 296,000 barrels of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
The automobile sector's gasoline consumption accounted for 51.8
percent of Venezuela's use of all liquid fuels last year.
</P>
<P>
Total supplies of hydrocarbons, including liquid fuels and
natural gas, showed a decrease of 1 percent last year compared
with 650,000 barrels per day in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Besides the shift of consumption from gasoline to natural gas,
higher fuel prices was another factor in the drop of gasoline use
in 1996, said the PDVSA statement available here today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
