<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina's Public Debt Jumps to Record High in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Argentina's public debt
increased by 10 percent to a record high of 97.105 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, a fiscal bulletin said today.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin, released by the economy ministry, reported that
68.841 billion dollars of the debt was related to public bonds and
securities in local and foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Multilateral institutions such as the Inter-American
Development Bank, the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund
and Fonpolata were in second place with 16.367 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country also owed 10.162 billion dollars to the Paris Club,
1.452 billion dollars to private banks and 283 million dollars to
other interests.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin reported that the country's public debt per capita
was 2,942 dollars by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's foreign debt increased sharply during the 1980s and
rose to 65 billion dollars in 1991, making it the third largest
debtor in the region.
</P>
<P>
During the early 1990s, the country was seriously in arrears to
its creditors. Agreements negotiated with banks reportedly had
collapsed due to the government's failure to fully implement its
policy commitments.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Argentina's foreign debt soared to 87 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
