<HEADLINE> Employment Rises in Havana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 35,000 jobs were created
in the capital city of Havana in 1996, although employment
continued to be a complex matter, a document by Cuba's labor
department said today.
</P>
<P>
The document said that despite a decrease of 2,836 contracts,
revitalization of activities provided 12,000 new jobs, especially
in construction, commerce, food, health and industry.
</P>
<P>
About 75 percent of those who sought employment received job
responses, and the commitment to providing labor for companies
with priority was fulfilled. 
</P>
