<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blast Mars Philippine Voters' Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- A home-made bomb exploded in a
voters' registration center in Metro Manila Monday, sending into
panic registrants for the May 12 Philippine community elections,
the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Police said the bomb exploded at 11:45 a.m. at a high school
used as a registration center just as the number of registrants
began to swell, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
But fortunately, no one was reported killed or injured by the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
Police said the bomb was hurled into the school by an
unidentified man who eluded arrest when registrants panicked.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Commission on Election (Comelec) described
Monday's registration as generally peaceful and orderly.
</P>
<P>
A total of 110,000 registration centers were put up by the
commission in more than 40,000 communities, known as "barangays"
in Filipino, throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Monday's registration was only in preparation for the May 12
polls for barangay officials. According to the Comelec, a general
registration will be conducted on June 14-21 for the 1998 national
elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
