<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Strengthens Efforts to Prevent Dengue Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Colombia spent about
260,000 U.S. dollars during the first two months of this year on a
campaign to prevent dengue disease in the country.
</P>
<P>
The campaign consists of speeding up fumigation and
biological control through a bacteria that destroys mosquito
larvae.
</P>
<P>
Health Ministry figures show 588 cases of hemorrhagic dengue
and 1,134 cases of classical dengue were reported in Colombia
between January and February.
</P>
<P>
Dengue is transmitted by the aedes aegypti mosquitos which
breed in warm climates.
</P>
<P>
Classical dengue has symptoms similar to bad flu accompanied by
fever, pain in the joints, vomiting and a lack of appetite. The
hemorrhagic variety causes bleeding in the gums and nose apart
from the symptoms of classical dengue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Club Chairman Loses Appeal Against 18-month Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The chairman of Spanish club
Deportivo de La Coruna lost his appeal Monday against an 18-month
ban slapped on him after he sought to overturn a Spanish
federation sanction in local courts.
</P>
<P>
FIFA upheld the February 10 decision of its disciplinary
committee, which suspended Augusto Cesar Lendoiro "from all
football activities" until August 1 1998.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the club was found "jointly liable" and ordered to
pay a fine of 100,000 Swiss Francs (71,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Lendoiro was suspended after he went against FIFA norms when he
appealed to an ordinary Spanish court to overturn a Spanish
federation order to close his club's stadium for one game, a
sanction imposed after a referee was hit by a coin during a match
last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
