<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Courier Survives Scares at Lipton Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Jim Courier, showing glimpses
of the fire that made him number one in the world five years ago,
won a tough third-round match at the 4.45 million US dollars
Lipton Championships on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Courier, ranked 26th and still struggling to regain the form
that won him two Australian and two French Open titles, fought
hard from 4-1 down in the third set to defeat talented Australian
lefthander Scott Draper 4-6, 6-1, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Draper, 22, won the first set 6-4 before going off the boil in
the second to drop it 6-1. But in the third set the Australian led
4-1 before Courier fought back and served out the match 6-4 as
Draper netted a backhand return.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Muster of Austria, the second seed, handed 166th-ranked
Tommy Haas a lesson on stadium court, defeating the 19-year old
German prospect 6-1, 6-2 in 52 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The women's second seed was upset when Arantxa Sanchez Vicario
of Spain played a lacklustre match with little-known Sandrine
Testud of France, going out 6-0, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Testud, ranked 29th, missed a match point at 5-4 but the
usually tigerish Spaniard could not force a comeback, going out on
the second match point with a netted forehand.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland was tested in her
fourth-round match before beating Russia's Elena Likhovtseva 6-3,
2-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Hingis will meet Mary Joe Fernandez in the quarter-finals.
Fernandez, ranked 12th, beat her former friend and doubles partner
Lindsay Davenport 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Monica Seles, the fourth seed, needed just 55 minutes to
advance past Asa Carlsson of Sweden 6-2, 6-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
