<HEADLINE> King Hussein to Visit Washington on April 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan will
meet with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington on April 1 for
talks on the Middle East peace process and bilateral issues, the
White House said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The King's trip was to have taken place two weeks ago, but was
postponed partly because Clinton had to undergo surgery for a knee
injury and partly because of regional developments, after a
Jordanian soldier opened fire on a group of Israeli schoolgirls,
killing seven of them and injuring six more.
</P>
<P>
The king's trip to Washington is the last in a series of
scheduled meetings in Washington between U.S. administration
officials and leaders of the core Middle East peace process
states.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was the first to come
to Washington at the end of February, and his visit was followed
by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak in March.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the trip comes at a time when Palestinians
in the West Bank clashed with Israeli soldiers for a fifth
consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
The clashes broke out last after Israeli began construction of
6,500 new housing units for Jews on the Jerusalem hilltop called
Abu Ghnaim.
</P>
<P>
The move outraged Palestinians, who want east Jerusalem as
the capital of a future state and resent Israeli attempts to
assert sovereignty over the entire city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
