<HEADLINE> Blue Chips Shoot Higher on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chip stocks in New York
shot higher over the final hour Monday as interest rates fell in
the bond market, but technology shares extended their recent
slide, led by steep drop by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 100.46 points to
6,905.25, wiping out a 21 point deficit in the earlier afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling 442.15 million
shares as against 534.36 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 6.79 to 790.89, and
the NYSE's composite index rose 3.20 to 416.00.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 11.42 to 1,242.65, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.28 to 587.94.
</P>
<P>
After trading nearly unchanged for much of the session, bonds
turned higher in the afternoon, sending long-term interest rates
lower and spurring the blue-chip rally.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft shares fell more than 4 percent as the most active
Nasdaq issue at the news that the updated version of the popular
Windows 95 operating system may reach the market after Christmas,
later than many people's expectation.
</P>
<P>
Other major technology shares also slid amid fears that the
delays at Microsoft would remove an incentive for consumers to buy
new computers or related products.
</P>
<P>
Many observers believe the central bank will nudge interest
rates higher Tuesday, slowing the economy as insurance against
inflationary pressures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
