<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central African Capital Returns to Calm as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 24 (Xinhua) -- The capital of the Central African
Republic Bangui remained calm today, while representatives of the
African peace-keeping force of MISAB and the mutinous soldiers
held a meeting under the mediation of Malian general Amadou
Toumani Toure.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which were aimed at ending the clashes between
MISAB's Chadian soldiers and the mutinous soldiers in which 11
people were killed and 30 wounded last weekend, went on until the
evening in a neutral field -- the residence of the archbishop of
Bangui, reported the Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Apart from General Toure, the MISAB military operation chief,
Colonel Talla Niang of Senegal, Captain Anicet Saule of the rebel
side and two other rebel officers took part in today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
The AFP quoted General Toure as saying that the meeting had
"allowed one to go ahead a little" and that it was decided that
"security measures would be reinforced in the field to avoid any
incident."
</P>
<P>
He said that the MISAB and the rebels will meet again on
Tuesday to continue their talks.
</P>
<P>
A rebel officer identified as Lieutenant Mbaye said that the
rebels wanted the immediate withdrawal of the Chadian contingent
from the MISAB, and the guarantee that they would enter the new
government of large openness as has been promised by President
Ange-Felix Patasse.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government of Chad today condemned what it
called "the repeated and unceasing attacks from the mutinous
soldiers, without pretext," against the Chadian soldiers in the
MISAB "who came to contribute to the maintenance of peace while
observing a strict neutrality."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on several kidnappings of Chadian merchants which
took place in Bangui over the past two days, the Chadian
government "warns the Central African government and mutinous
soldiers once more that it would not tolerate any more that the
Chadian citizens be the innocent victims of an internal conflict
in the Central African Republic."
</P>
<P>
The Chadian government said that it would send troop
reinforcement to Bangui to back up the Chadian soldiers already
stationed there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
