<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Narcotics-Related Corruption Serious in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Narcotics-related corruption
in the United States is serious and growing at a time when the
latter accusing some other countries of not making enough efforts
to stop drug-trafficking, the New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
At least 46 Federal, state, and local law-enforcement officials
have been indicted on or convicted of drug-related corruption
charges in the last three years in the border states of
California, Arizona, New Mexico and Texas, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The cases were only those that related to drugs transported
across the border by land and they represent only a small part of
the problem, Federal law-enforcement officials were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Many federal officials fear that the problem will grow worse as
drug dealers have become more brazen and the volume and value of
drugs moving across the U.S.-Mexico border have skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
The Customs Service reported that at five border crossings on
the California-Mexico border, marijuana seizures increased to
3,518 in 1996 from 2,490 in 1995. A total of 272,000 pounds of
marijuana were seized last year at the section of border.
</P>
<P>
The Customs Service report indicates that in 1996, around
550,000 pounds of marijuana, 45,000 pounds of cocaine and 500
pounds of heroin were seized at border crossings between Mexico
and the United States. Among the seized drugs, marijuana
increased by more than 25 percent and heroin rose by more than
150 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that serious corruption encouraged drug
traffickers to get drugs into the United States through legal
ports of entry instead of trying to bring them across at remote
border areas.
</P>
<P>
In Zapata County, Texas, most of the courty's leaders,
including the county judge, the sheriff and the clerk, were
convicted of or pleaded guilty in Federal court to charges of
aiding the international drug trafficking, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Corruption of law-enforcement officials has become a corrosive
by product of the vast river of drugs that pours into the United
States, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
