<DOCNO> XIE19970325.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zairean Gov't Resigns, Presidential Party Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, March 24 (Xinhua) -- Zaire's prime minister Kengo wa
Dondo and his government today presented their resignation to
President Mobutu Sese Seko, who "has taken note of the act," the
Zairean official television announced today.
</P>
<P>
The television reported that the prime minister "presented in
the afternoon his resignation and that of his government to
Marshal Mobutu who took note of the act and asked him to look
after the current affairs until the establishment of a new
government."
</P>
<P>
This morning, Mobutu also took note of a parliamentary motion
adopted on March 18 and calling for the sacking of the prime
minister and his government.
</P>
<P>
This motion was contested by the government which termed it
anti-constitutional because the quorum of the votes by 553
councillors had not been attained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the presidential party of Zaire, le Mouvement
Populaire de la Revolution (MPR), today declared its readiness to
open talks with the rebels of Laurent-Desire Kabila.
</P>
<P>
MPR's vice-president, Banza Mukalay, who is also vice prime
minister, said that his party is ready to negotiate with Kabila
"if it is the price of peace."
</P>
<P>
The Zairean government and army had refused to hold talks with
the rebels in the past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
